commit_message:
Use consistent RabbitMQ settings across guide.

Use consistent values for rabbit_host, rabbit_userid, and
rabbit_password across the guide. Previously there were a number of
variations, particularly of the host and password values.

In a subsequent patch I intend to cover off the fact that RabbitMQ
is installed/configured in at least two locations. I may depending
on feedback also end up adding an instruction to set the guest
user's password in which case a further update to rabbit_password
will be required.

I think just getting the initial values to base this work on consistent,
as I am proposing in this patch, is a good start.

Where programlisting elements that were touched use "bash" as the
language I have also flipped them to "ini".

Change-Id: Ie3779db58f8a397753a9a2409bd838ea97a87568

commit_message:
Use consistent address for Qpid

Consistently use the controller host name for Qpid. Files from
the old basic install guide which are slated for removal were
left untouched.

Change-Id: I7e0c6a8239a8179db303cfa18821e7f7f799d5c5

Remove novaclient keypairs get monkey patch

We're now depend on novaclient that contains this patch.
Additionally, we should always monkey patch _add_details.

Included 'cinder extend' command and updated command reference for cinder

CLI chapter. Also updated the command reference appendix section

Add Ceilometer install

This adds an initial install of ceilometer to the install guide.

This has not been tested.

Also adds stub sections for adding agents/setting up notification to things.

commit_message:
Fix policies

Policy file contained malformed content so the policy
engine failed to parse it. That was the reason of rejecting
all requests, if authentication was enabled.

This patch also updates policies to get rid of unused policies
and use GenericCheck to check for admin API.

After changes mentioned above some unused code appeared in
ironic.common.policy and so it was cleaned up.

Closes-bug: #1236371
Change-Id: Ie1dbda11561a9e7068d240a19f9fb98eae121c94

subject: Hide settings/change password on keystone v3
messages:
[{'account_id': 4264, 'date': '2013-10-11 09:28:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 4978, 'date': '2013-10-11 10:28:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

With the Keystone patch for the same bug ( https://review.openstack.org/#/c/50962/ ), it looks like now by default it is not possible anymore for a regular user (non-admin) to update their own password, and Horizon redirects to the main page with a permission error. Unfortunately I don't see a similar "Update Own Password" method in V3 than existed in V2, and I'm not familiar enough with Keystone to know if it's only missing in the client or would require more work.

https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/blob/master/keystoneclient/v2_0/users.py#L69
https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/blob/master/keystoneclient/v3/users.py

Perhaps for now, we should disable the 'Change password' panel when Keystone v3 is in use? (Or use the new RBAC permissions to only show it if it is usable by the current user.)

Additionally, it would be nice to get a proper form error explaining the initial password is wrong, rather than "Error: Unauthorized: Unable to change password." though maybe that can come later.'}, {'account_id': 4264, 'date': '2013-10-11 12:28:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thank you Julie for your comments.
The question is here: how to fix a fundamental issue in Keystone client-wise?

Changing the password as a user will (sooner or later, when the corresponding keystone patch is merged) require admin privileges.

I assume, the best solution is to disable the panel.'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-10-11 15:01:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Julie- that's correct, there is currently no parity for v2's "Update Own Password" method in v3 (it's missing from both the client and the API). I'd like to add one in icehouse.

Matthias- I'll be happy to tackle the client-side implementation once we have the API spec'd for v3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-11 16:08:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Hide settings/change password on keystone v3

When using keystone v3, it was possible to change the user
password without knowing the old password.

Change-Id: I2e3721f9c8a1de4b9a5f85b230432844d2c83507
Closes-Bug: 1237989

commit_message:
Moved quota headroom calculations into quota_reserve

Moved headroom calculations into quota_reserve and modified headroom
calculations to take into account -ve quota limits (unlimited) on
cores and ram.

Updated test cases to generate OverQuota exceptions with new headroom
parameter.

Change-Id: I855b0cad495182c5c4ee42b2acf5eedd198557b5
Closes-Bug: #1224453 min_count ignored for instance create

Applied style changes based on reviewer comments.

Change-Id: I07b3456428e386c051a4e03ebfb06c3b3e079a77

commit_message:
set user_update policy to admin_required

This changes the default policy.json to prevent users from changing
their own attributes such as password, name, or default_project_id.

Closes-Bug: 1237989
Change-Id: I7de5fff3d72a76b78113e289c57a9fac2096395f

commit_message:
Use abstract base class for identity driver

Use the abc module for managing abstract base classes in the driver
layer.

bp abstract-base-class-drivers

commit_message:

commit_message:
Remove `--short` git option

`pull-tools` script fails on Ubuntu 12.04 because it's git does not
support `--short` option in `git symbolic-ref` command.
To fix it, `--short` option was removed and `cut` command to shorten the
name was added.

Change-Id: Ia7be559b7edd0d78da40ed49e88fd191c21ec13c

commit_message:
Separate out metadata and default routes.

With the host routes extension we can access the metadata service
without having to mess about with the default route, increasing
performance. Yay. Only works for single L2 networks (because any
router seeing traffic for 169.254.169.254 will discard it unless
explicitly configured. Configuring that is a use case for neutron
baremetal...

Related-Bug: #1239481
Change-Id: If434cc2e71ec9ee71c6e75b5aa4eff0a351d107b

commit_message:
Build end user image during overcloud deploy.

This reduces overall cycle time by exploiting some natural
parallelism. On small machines it may reduce performance if we exceed
the concurrent available capacity, but most production environments
will have enough ram to be building in tmpfs, and 2 cores - enough for
one to build the image and one to be driving deployment logic.

Change-Id: I314c5784bba6cd4efdf7b4a80759db844857d0b0

with their desired version advertisement.

commit_message:
Fix NovaObject versioning attribute usage

A typo made early in the object prototyping process has meant that
all objects thus far have been exposing a version of '1.0' because
the base object has been using an attribute of 'version'. The
object implementations have been exposing a 'VERSION' attribute
with their desired version advertisement.

Since we are still relatively early in the process of deploying
objects, the impact from this should be relatively minor, although
it is important to get this fixed ASAP before any incompatible
object changes are made.

Change-Id: If9154dc663111f304f72ef7f6f37c465e84ff504
Closes-bug: #1239709

with HEAD which already contains the object metadata.

commit_message:
Handle unicode at the caching layer more elegantly

This patchset resolves an issue where in some cases unicode would
cause the cache key generator to raise a UnicodeEncodeError due to
the name/value being outside of the standard ascii character set.
Included is a fix to the cache backend debug code to utilize repr
for passing the keys/values to the logger.

Tests in test_backend provided by chenxiao <chenxiao@cn.ibm.com>

Closes-bug: 1237892
Change-Id: I4df1c9eb6b4a1367defdbb6bcbcd1f1f992348e5

commit_message:
cisco/nexus plugin doesn't create port for router interface

Fixes bug 1234826

This fix adds a "nexus_l3_enable" configuration boolean for the
Cisco Nexus plugin. When this config boolean is set to False (default),
then the Nexus switches are only used for L2 switching/segmentation, and
layer 3 functionality is deferred to the OVS subplugin / network
control node. If this config boolean is set to True, layer 3
functionality, e.g. switch virtual interfaces, are supported on
the Nexus switches. (Note that layer 3 functionality is not supported
on all versions/models Nexus switches.)

Some other things addressed with this fix:
- The l3_port_check keyword argument which is optionally passed to the
  Cisco plugin's delete_port method was not being forwarded on to the
  OVS (sub) plugin. This keyword argument needs to be forwarded to OVS
  e.g. when the delete_port is being done in the context of a
  router interface delete (whereby l3_port_check==False).
- UT test cases are added for new "nexus_l3_enable" config, which
  exercise router interface add/delete.
- The Cisco test_network_plugin.py module is refactored/reorganized
  in order to cleanly add a new router interface test class.
- The test_model_update_port_rollback test case was yielding a false
  positive result (device_owner was not being passed to self.port).

Change-Id: I994b2b82769ea5e10e50dbe3a223d1518e99f714

commit_message:
Helpers to save flow factory in metadata

This change adds new helpers that, taken together, allow to resume
the flows having nothing but flow detail at hands. First one,
load_from_factory, gets flow factory function as a parameter and
saves its fully qualified name and arguments to flow metadata. Others
can be used to re-create the flow using that metadata, and load
it into engine.

Change-Id: Ia3cd989b3b0388ec0a9f09fe527f768eec5cc904

commit_message:
Setup admin and end user accounts in the overcloud.

While ongoing management is a matter of API use, we have a specific
use case for automation: we want controlled access to just TripleO
ATC's (vs self-signup via a portal), as part of the TripleO CD cloud.
I decided not to do something fancy for passwords (like GPG encrypting
to the user) and instead just capture an initial password for the user
on disk, which any admin can log in and give to the user, because
thats sufficient to get folk going. Until we have state preservation
we need to recreate the users each time, which is another reason to
keep the passwords around: that way it's not new every time for users.

Change-Id: Ie5b0f92f204af467fe3159cc2a05860d01608310

commit_message:
xenapi: max out VCPU count

Give as much VCPUs to the DevStack machine as possible. First asking
xenapi about its CPU count, and as a fallback, count the CPUs in dom0.
This should result in faster test runs.

Change-Id: I1ffb99ecd435f1d7eb5754fe9cd99f0e8ceae6dc

commit_message:
Adding value for lock_path in configuration file

Now oslo code include new lockutils. According this code
if lock_path is not set in configuration file, will be
raised Error message.

So for updating lockutils in cinder project is needed
lock_path definition in configuration file.

Change-Id: I413f0a2ccec0f9d9e06acaa8cc06c41206d9dcc2

commit_message:
Correct logging_context_format_string for Heat

We should use "tenant" and "user" instead of "project_name" and
"user_name" by calling setup_colorized_logging with these parameters.

Change-Id: I47820c890bf4585e7c8f64c41f48d7576ca56862
Closes-Bug: 1237314

'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2013-10-01 13:11:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

This is a really good start Dean, but one thing this doesn't address which I'd like to see it address is the ability to configure arbitrary configuration files, rather than just core files. For instance, with Neutron and Modular Layer 2 (ML2), depending on how many MechanismDrivers you load, each one will have it's own configuration file. You changes here don't cover that use case, but I believe they could be extended to cover it. So this doesn't cover the use case which this review [1[ was hoping to address.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40882/"}, {'account_id': 2888, 'date': '2013-10-08 13:38:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

great improvment, especially to configure vxlan section of ML2 plugin, when it is used with linuxbridge. 
I had an issues, with a multi-host config. We are used to only enable services q-agt,n-cpu on compute node, but we have to had "enable services neutron" so that ml2_conf.ini will be populated with the [neutron] section.
"enable services neutron" is not mandatory on the controller.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-10-08 19:40:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Kyle, you actually can change any file on the system using this, the group determines _if/when_ a particular section is evaluated, not which files it can manipulate.  That said, it appears to not have quite the if/then capability that you are looking for here.

To handle the MechanismDrivers, as it sits you would just have to have all of them that you expect prepared and let the config files be modified even if the driver is not loaded.  I gather that the selection of MechanismDrivers is a start-time decision and the requirement that all of local.conf be consistent with the configured services seems reasonable to me.  Am I missing anything here?  It does seem like the ability to select a different local.conf file to use on the stack.sh command line might be useful now.

Matthieu, multi-host has always been a weakness in DevStack as the localrc has always needed to be custom for each host.  That is still the case here, and as I mentioned above, the group name doesn't have to match the owner of the file you are modifying.  If you need to modify ml2_config.ini and only q-agt is enabled, then put q-agt as the group name on those hosts."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-10-08 19:42:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Add meta-config via local.conf

This defines a new local.conf file that is designed to take the place of all
of the 'pass-through'[1] configuration options that have been defined in DevStack.

* new local.conf file can contain multiple config file settings to be
  merged in to existing project config files
* localrc can be embedded into local.conf and will auto-extract if
  localrc does not exist
* Adds functions get_meta_section(), get_meta_section_files(),
  merge_config_file() and merge_config_group()
* Adds EXTRA_OPTS, EXTRA_BAREMETAL_OPTS, Q_DHCP_EXTRA_DEFAULT_OPTS and
  Q_SRV_EXTRA_DEFAULT_OPTS to the deprecated warning list at the end of stack.sh

[1] Pass-through options are those that do not configure or change DevStack's behaviour
but simply set a value in a project config file.  This includes most of the EXTRA_XXX_OPTS
configuration variables.

Change-Id: I367cadc86116621e9574ac203aafdab483d810d3

Add a persistence util logbook formatting function

It is quite useful to be able to dump what is in a
logbook in a human readable format so this adds a
helper utility function to do just this.

Change-Id: I84d8a9caf531de018fb361211624fc5b8c030260

commit_message:
Save with the same connection

Instead of 2 different connections, one
for saving the flow detail and then one
for saving the task detail just use one
connection for both.

Change-Id: I68315a6c201325bb154f5ab5fc69a3824055c912

it is nicer to have this function be named
closer to what it returns (the graph of tasks
to be executed) as well as make it a property
since it is more of a property of the engine.

'}]
commit_message:
Rename get_graph() -> execution_graph

Instead of having a generic get_graph()
it is nicer to have this function be named
closer to what it returns (the graph of tasks
to be executed) as well as make it a property
since it is more of a property of the engine.

Change-Id: I4bb458b1069d7e6877f1cc51d42bfc0d8c751951

[{'created': '2013-10-14 17:17:25.000000000', 'message': 'Make openreviews generate quartiles instead of just median.

By reporting 1,2,3 quartiles instead of just the 2nd (median) we can get a
better insight into what the distribution looks like. For example if
the median is good, but the 1st quartile is very low and the 3rd is very
high it means we have some patches would be waiting much longer then
others, but our average(median) may still be good.

Change-Id: I3427e562ab39dc6915ac0d2e42347e0d6e0123bc
'}]
commit_message:
Make openreviews generate quartiles instead of just median.

By reporting 1,2,3 quartiles instead of just the 2nd (median) we can get a
better insight into what the distribution looks like. For example if
the median is good, but the 1st quartile is very low and the 3rd is very
high it means we have some patches would be waiting much longer then
others, but our average(median) may still be good.

Change-Id: I3427e562ab39dc6915ac0d2e42347e0d6e0123bc

[{'created': '2013-10-10 18:12:15.000000000', 'message': "Replaces mox with mock in api's unit tests

OpenStack is moving unit tests from mox to mock for python3.3 compatibility.
This replaces mox with mock in api's unit tests.

It also fixes a slight problem with ..test_nodes.TestPut.test_power_state_in_progress().
mox was generating the exception (due to a second call to .update_node()), not
the ironic code. This is because objects.Node.get_by_uuid() returns a different
node (that gets its state changed) and the original node never gets the change.
When it is mocked to return the same node, the expected exception is raised by
ironic.api.controllers.v1.node.NodePowerStateController.put().

Change-Id: If734fb4c9a4a386ccc37a1336dbd41e3121a5ef4
"}]
commit_message:
Replaces mox with mock in api's unit tests

OpenStack is moving unit tests from mox to mock for python3.3 compatibility.
This replaces mox with mock in api's unit tests.

It also fixes a slight problem with ..test_nodes.TestPut.test_power_state_in_progress().
mox was generating the exception (due to a second call to .update_node()), not
the ironic code. This is because objects.Node.get_by_uuid() returns a different
node (that gets its state changed) and the original node never gets the change.
When it is mocked to return the same node, the expected exception is raised by
ironic.api.controllers.v1.node.NodePowerStateController.put().

Change-Id: If734fb4c9a4a386ccc37a1336dbd41e3121a5ef4

commit_message:
Fixed UI bug with broken plugins page

Horizon requires id from returned objects but Savanna plugins
don't have such ones. Actually this code was in savanna client
when it was in savanna-dashboard code:
https://github.com/openstack/savanna-dashboard/blob/0.3a1/savannadashboard/api/plugins.py#L26-L30

Fixes bug#1239676

Change-Id: I6326d0478f5ddbfc4258450e6c0da88cd518de62

commit_message:
Harden version checking for boto

Simple string comparison is not effective for version checking.
Let's switch to using pkg_resources.parse_version and compare
the tuples. Per review feedback, enabling the code path for
2.13 as well. Originally we had handled this by excluding
2.13 from requirements. With this we should be able to removing
the exclusion for 2.13 from global requirements.

Change-Id: Ie047f7201d8e6a9a9641000d387c4312506f49b1
Closes-Bug: #1239220

'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2013-10-13 12:31:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Matt, why was this done? It would be great if we could have better commit messages explaining *why* something was done and not just *what* was done. Also, I'm not a huge fan of approving one's own patches, especially in such a short time period."}, {'account_id': 26, 'date': '2013-10-14 15:55:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sorry for the terse commit message, I had a more verbose commit message in another commit that I had abandoned. 

Vagabond was blocking any commits to openstack-chef-repo because the gem was unable to build from the GitHub source. I pinged the IRC channel about it and a couple of core reviewers directly, and got Craig to review it. Since Vagabond is not currently actually used to gate the repo with tests and we're not using a version from RubyGems, I pushed the review through to unblock the other PRs (some of which had been reviewed prior to being abandoned because they were blocked by Vagabond).

I apologize for pushing my own reviews through, I was growing impatient with what I considered a fundamentally broken gate blocking other reviews. I definitely want to get Vagabond added back, especially if we can make it actually part of the gate for the openstack-chef-repo."}]

if the user changes the ownership on the files, I'm not sure why we'd go back and rechange them"}, {'account_id': 8641, 'date': '2013-10-14 15:23:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sean, I address the problem for below scenario:
- Update some configuration of the config file by vim, thus I change the file's ownership.
- After several days, some services are down.
- I don't want to bother to manual fix it, thus I re-run ./stack.sh

Then the error complains.

As a conclusion, devstack need to update these configuration files, when re-run ./stack.sh"}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-10-14 15:43:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

This change un-does the proper ownership on the rootwrap files.

I totally understand that security and devstack are things that usually don't get said in the same breath, but we shouldn't be making that worse..."}, {'account_id': 8641, 'date': '2013-10-14 15:45:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-10 22:13:58.000000000', 'message': 'make sure devstack change owner for all files in /etc/*/conf

Currently devstack only change the ownership of /etc/*/conf,
without changing its children.

This will incur permission denied error, when re-run ./stack.sh.

commit_message:
make sure devstack change owner for all files in /etc/*/conf

Currently devstack only change the ownership of /etc/*/conf,
without changing its children.

This will incur permission denied error, when re-run ./stack.sh.

Check bugs.launchpad.net for detail explanation
Closes-Bug: #1238294

Change-Id: If91092caf266a88168362ae350bd54c8c63f522c

commit_message:
Improve error message for ssh

This message was always returning "SSHPowerDriver unknown virt_type
(None)", it was suppose to at least shows the inputed virt_type value
by the user. This patch fix it making the message more user-friendly by
showing what was the valued inputed by the user + the supported values
by that module.

Change-Id: I92a78dfe065d9a38fab718bbc710b1adf933ee41

remove code duplication in clean.sh

When source functions of lib, provide a comon loop.
It find all files directed located in lib directory,

then source them one by one

commit_message:
Rework redirections of old content

Add redirect for old locations.

Fix redirects to go to current location.

Use redirectmatch for those guides that are completely reorganized
so that all links will go to the index.html page.

Change-Id: I59c61b77d6f11cc577930e389dfb21fec91644ad

for havana.

commit_message:
set user_update policy to admin_required

This changes the default policy.json to prevent users from changing
their own attributes such as password, name, or default_project_id.

Closes-Bug: 1237989
Change-Id: I7de5fff3d72a76b78113e289c57a9fac2096395f

commit_message:
No need to restart Web-server now to see changes in dynamic UI.

Workflow is simpler now: edit form definition YAML-file, save it,
reload the form it affects. Voila!

Implements: feature MRN-1147
Cherry-picked from dc78dc3b68705b4f1826864067731d31d4d603b0

Change-Id: I72d68c17b829f9252560ecd01335656ffba0b262

commit_message:
XenAPI: Fix translation of metadetails in aggregates

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/43157/ added a translation from the sqlalchemy model to
the instance object replacing metadetails with metadata.

This added more traces in general for XenAPI (when we queried whether we were using
aggregates) and actually broke the host aggregate functionality

Change-Id: I87195753931945b6e1ecf75bc81575a6fa03068e
Closes-bug: 1232179

commit_message:
keystone client changes in AuthProtocol made our test cases failing

class AuthProtocol from python-keystoneclient project has been
changed. It no longer has the member auth_protocol, auth_port and
auth_host, our test cases need to be changed to test against other
members like auth_uri.

Change-Id: I3af86bb773fef80054bb0ad3820e1b8510bf67cb
fixes: bug #1231491
(cherry picked from commit 20dd735694f1f913fec83f2ae679aedc57379716)

reload the form it affects. Voila!

Implements: feature MRN-1147

commit_message:
Adding 'download_image' policy enforcement to image cache middleware

Currently image cache middleware not care 'download_image' policy, the
enforcement caused user receive empty content but with HTTP 200 code
rather than 403 when client attempt to download image using v2 API. And
the real Forbidden exception be logged in glance-api log which image
application action raised. The end user is confused by this behavior.

Fixes bug: 1235378

Related-Id: Ibaa7ccf8613ee3cce4cb6a72e3206a2c94122222
Change-Id: I6ce09c764436da52ed0a5219c33ae0fb542dd3f8
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>
(cherry picked from commit a50bfbf490fd354d08abd25b67aaab83b2a17a85)

commit_message:
Specify distro release in fedora image name

The fedora element downloads the latest available image so presumably
will jump to F20 once available. Probably causing several days (weeks?)
of busted stuff. Of course it will be impossible to know when all users
of the elements are ready to switch but the least we can do is allow a
little time as a buffer.

This commit ties it down to a specific version which can then be updated
when the consumers of this element are ready. This allso follows the
same pattern as the ubuntu element.

Change-Id: I15c8e15a66e8af1bd152c27144acbc55af9da88e

Use kvm for the cd-overcloud.

It defaults to qemu in devtest_overcloud, and we definitely don't want
qemu in prod.

commit_message:
Support working with neutron host-routes.

If there is a neutron host-route for metadata, we shouldn't try to
replace the metadata route - instead just change the default route.

Change-Id: I27ab5057b32fcab00e4465913f03336125cbd665

commit_message:
Set nova's default_floating_pool setting.

Without this the floating-ip extension looks for a neutron network
called 'nova' to handle floating IP requests.

Change-Id: If04bb47b2d2df4e87d0dd724c4598b94f5c97872
Fixes-Bug: #1239450

commit_message:
xenapi: simplify _migrate_disk_resizing_up

Previously it called get_vdi_for_vm_safely but there was no need,
because we already get all the VDI information we need from
snapshot_attached_here.

This will make it easer to expand the method to include the migration of
ephemeral disks.

Part of blueprint xenapi-migrate-ephemeral-disks
Change-Id: I4e0dd1a875ee7e194d38016ff49296a360627aea

commit_message:
xenapi: revert on _migrate_disk_resizing_up error

_migrate_disk_resizing_up now follows similar pattern to
_migrate_disk_resizing_down.

This involves using the @step decorator to report progress and rolling
back if any errors occur while migrating the disks to the destination
host.

Part of blueprint xenapi-migrate-ephemeral-disks
Change-Id: I2557357a4f3502f991a5d187c2ecf7ffeb22286e

commit_message:
xenapi: make _migrate_disk_resizing_up use @step

Make use of the step decorator into _migrate_disk_resizing_up to make it
more consistent with _migrate_disk_resizing_up.

Also add some extra unit tests to help lock down this process with unit
tests.

Part of blueprint xenapi-migrate-ephemeral-disks
Change-Id: I395b8e27380649c667bb8d891802532ee3ab746b

commit_message:
Add boto special casing for param changes in 2.13

boto 2.13 has some interface changes with the get_http_connection
call which adds port as a non optional parameter *in the middle of*
existing non optional parameters. It's a special kind of incompatible
change.

We are already special casing around boto in the unit tests, lets
just do more of that if we are running on a newer version.

(cherry picked from commit 1ce493b9e4e0c381146287161ab2a3c75f1fc603)

Change-Id: I62f5d4ef5cfa5577015a521a5d161086546a4125
Co-Authored-By: Sean Dague <sdague@linux.vnet.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dansmith@redhat.com>

Nova defaults to trying to allocate floating ips from a neutron
network called 'nova' but we called our external one ext-net (which
various Neutron documentation uses), so we need to override it or the
nova floating-ips extension isn't usable [without explicitly setting a

commit_message:
Add metadata for the nova floating-ips extension.

Nova defaults to trying to allocate floating ips from a neutron
network called 'nova' but we called our external one ext-net (which
various Neutron documentation uses), so we need to override it or the
nova floating-ips extension isn't usable [without explicitly setting a
pool in the API calls].

Partial-Bug: #1239450
Change-Id: I1ef78642bdc1f19d25422961350e4f02a8f6c16f

commit_message:
Ignore irrelevant secgroup form field errors

When cleaning data from in the security group rule form, remove any
associated error messages that are not related to the actual fields
being saved.  If we are setting a value derived from another field, also
delete the error message associated with that field.

Change-Id: I1eb4835ea2368b62374f230c6293062a2340980d
Closes-Bug:1237128

commit_message:
VMware tests: replace assertEquals with assertEqual

In Python 2.6, both assertEqual and assertEquals are
convenience aliases to failUnlessEqual.

In Python 3, failUnlessEqual is explicitly deprecated.

This is part of blueprint assertequal

Change-Id: I4121817277c11e82e0ed63ef8bd1c1e4c951a018

commit_message:
Respects TOCI_REPOREF_* variables for tripleo subprojects too

If TOCI_REPOREF_* variables are used to set specific commit hash
for basic tripleo repos (diskimage-builder, tripleo-image-elements...),
then respect this variable when fetching repos in toci_git.sh.

Change-Id: I2c32ce91bc30992a072ab9ccff6ec0e8aa2c3242

generate-interfaces-file.sh was always intended to be idempotent, but
the ifquery call either made no sense before, or makes no sense on

commit_message:
Fix dhcp-all-interfaces idempotency.

generate-interfaces-file.sh was always intended to be idempotent, but
the ifquery call either made no sense before, or makes no sense on
current Debian-like distros. It is now fixed to be idempotent.

Change-Id: Ie367de776f6fb4331fe81d3e45dd874bea3cf462

commit_message:
Remove instance_info_cache_update() from conductor

After network api was converted to use InfoCache object it no longer
depends on the conductor instance_info_cache_update() method.

This change removes this method from conductor and in addition removes
conductor parameter in calls to network api from within compute manager,
previously needed by the @refrech_cache() decorator in network api for
its calls to this same conductor method.

Change-Id: I5bb535062b5f5948e2b6ba1daa089f3d93471394

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-11 22:12:15.000000000', 'message': 'Xenapi: set hostname when performing a network reset

The hostname is removed from the metadata on Xen to address an
issue where windows instances get renamed on reboot. This
becomes a problem when a network reset is called for instances
using the agent communication mechanism. In that case the
agent will incorrectly rename the host. Thus the
hostname needs to be set prior and cleared after a network reset.

The setting of the metadata params also need to be atomic so
locking was added that matches to the locking provided by
other data (network metadata).

Fixes bug 1236877

Change-Id: I473870994c826f85a7c6ec1448171c4e4ee40ff0
'}]
commit_message:
Xenapi: set hostname when performing a network reset

The hostname is removed from the metadata on Xen to address an
issue where windows instances get renamed on reboot. This
becomes a problem when a network reset is called for instances
using the agent communication mechanism. In that case the
agent will incorrectly rename the host. Thus the
hostname needs to be set prior and cleared after a network reset.

The setting of the metadata params also need to be atomic so
locking was added that matches to the locking provided by
other data (network metadata).

Fixes bug 1236877

Change-Id: I473870994c826f85a7c6ec1448171c4e4ee40ff0

commit_message:
Move `utils.hash_file` -> `imagecache._hash_file`

`hash_file` is only used by `imagecache` so it doesn't make sense (yet) for it
to be included in utils.

Change-Id: I2f4d1deb03e4afceb911ef4b6d6ae6760ddca225

commit_message:
Log which filter failed when on log level INFO

If log level is set to INFO,only see a log message about nova-schedule
attempting to build n instances then a log message about setting the
state to error when the scheduler fails to schedule an instance due to
a filter returning 0 hosts.It may be useful to see which filterreturns 0
host for operator.

Close-bug: #1226334

Change-Id: I7564a8ab093895d1f9db357009aac294783a808b

commit_message:
hyperv tests: replace assertEquals with assertEqual

In Python 2.6, both assertEqual and assertEquals are
convenience aliases to failUnlessEqual.

In Python 3, failUnlessEqual is explicitly deprecated.

This is part of blueprint assertequal

Change-Id: I9c61bb5b3b6bd40018371aa5f17a3a96cff41a55

commit_message:
Remove readable permissions for "other"

Services installed by os-svc-install tend to have sensitive information
in their config directory and shouldn't be world readable. This commit
sets appropriate permissions on the config directory in os-svc-install.

Before this commit suitable permissions were set on the nova and heat
config directories but keystone and glance were readable without any
specific permissions.

Change-Id: I9d7a1e38742f0eb2fb02bbfc10ac22a195a46f36

This certainly makes sense in the context of the tripleo-cd cloud.  But I'm not sure I like it applied globally like this to anyone that uses the heat-engine element.

What would you think about a separate element, heat-engine-purge-deleted (or similar) that just added this cron job?

I'm not really convicted enough to go +1 or -1.  Just a comment for now :)."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-10-08 23:08:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Sounds like this is a heat bug? Is there a bug number for it? (-production defaults-)."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-10-09 04:09:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

There's an entire blueprint on multi-engine that is stalled out because it is hard:

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/heat/+spec/multiple-engines

Not sure what the bug in Heat would be. When we have multi-engine, only doing one delete on one server at a time is just an optimization. If we ran it on n servers then the first one would do all the deletes (in a transaction) and the other two would block on that one's locks, then run very quickly because there are very few rows left that exceed the age."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-10-12 21:33:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Oh James I never responded to your comment.

So _something_ must do these purges, or the database will grow indefinitely. I am disinclined to decouple these until a concrete alternative approach is identified.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-10-12 21:36:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add purge_deleted cron job to heat-engine

Heat-engine is currently only single-host, so this works in that model.
When heat-engine adds scale-out, we will probably want to do something
to make sure that only one of these runs, though it won't hurt to just
run a few of them at one time.

Change-Id: I2fe92489404e7ae490d78323d944703ec7d19007

commit_message:
Setup overcloud user and administrative accounts.

To avoid polluting incubator with the cd cloud specific knowledge,
like the networking, we pass in the list of users and administrators.
Note that we could just make this hidden, but that makes it harder to
introspect. The incubator code will consider these lists authoritative
and just consult deploy-environment state for the passwords to inject
for users without accounts in the cloud.

Change-Id: I1a6cf06d1a72f4fee6ab198ab4db5d803fbb7202

commit_message:
When using a specific public IP set endpoints too.

Otherwise the deployment network - the undercloud - gets registered as
the endpoint, which is an epic fail.

commit_message:
Fixes inconsistency in flavors list with marker

Flavors list with marker is supposed to use flavorid as the marker since this is
the only id attribute the users can see, but it was using id (the confusion was
probably caused by the fact that flavorid attribute shows up to the user as id).

The change on db unit test shows makes the bug evident, and justify the changes
on the filter_by criteria.

Fixes bug 1226698

Change-Id: I3ffa636febb63be796fffc94be6486bf74e8239b

commit_message:
xenapi: Set networking defaults

As XenServer runs devstack in a domU, special network interface defaults
need to be specified. This change moves the default network interface
settings from the driver to the nova library.

Fixes bug 1237461

Change-Id: I4da676971e9c311cdb3af0757168fa806a3d69d5

commit_message:
Fix vmwareapi driver get_diagnostics calls

The vmware driver is calling vmops.get_info for both the get_info and
get_diagnostics APIs which is wrong since they should be returning
different information.  Given the hypervisor support matrix doesn't list
the vmware driver as supporting the nova diagnostics API, it seems this
was just an oversight.

This patch changes the driver code to call the vmops.get_diagnostics
method which raises NotImplementedError.  It also fixes the tests to
actually ensure covers get_diagnostics for both the ESX driver and the
VC driver.

Closes-Bug: #1237622

Change-Id: I0c9015f1f7d5dd219548196de479e87e878ea0fd

When reboot a suspended/stopped VM without hard option on KVM,
the KVM libvirt driver failed to soft reboot the VM, then after
wait 120s, libvirt driver try to hard reboot the VM and finally
succeed.

For a  suspended/stopped VM instance on KVM, its domain id is -1,
but soft reboot did not handle the case to reboot a such VM.

commit_message:
compute api should throw exception if soft reboot invalid state VM

When user perform soft reboot to a VM which in suspended/paused/
stopped/error state, nova compute api should throw exception for
such state.

Change-Id: Ic365c6360f6b7407d9de0dac6ff1093484692cf4
Closes-Bug: #1236930

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-03 01:43:16.000000000', 'message': "VMware: fixes failure attaching iscsi cinder volumes

VMware drivers fail to attach a iSCSI backed cinder volume with an
error 'unable to find iscsi targets' because the underlying
retrieval api was updated to a newer version (see bug 1183654) but
not it's usage in volume_util. This is a regression over Grizzly
release. Also, the api call fails to specify the iscsi server
location (referred in the code as target portal) to retrieve
targets. Both are critical for the existing feature to work.

Fixes: bug #1193980

Change-Id: Ic2d1dc800fa10295a4d7312fbeeaa0e16d792755

commit_message:
VMware: fix regression attaching iscsi cinder volumes

VMware drivers fail to attach a iSCSI backed cinder volume with an
error 'unable to find iscsi targets' because the underlying
retrieval api was updated to a newer version but not it's usage in
volume_util (see commit e331287cdd1300878bfb9bbb3630889370e5fa72).
This is a regression over Grizzly release.

Fixes: bug #1193980

Change-Id: Ic2d1dc800fa10295a4d7312fbeeaa0e16d792755

commit_message:
Introduce Authentication Plugins

This extracts the basic auth plugin from the v2 and v3 client. It is not
possible to pass an auth plugin at this point. The client indicates the
plugin class relevant to it and it is constructed purely for the
authentication request then discarded after the response has been
extracted.

Change-Id: I3ed5985a7c28ab0a8a2659f0b0dc03f5b54fd949
Part of: blueprint auth-plugins

Leaving at 0 for now as I'm not entirely sure of the test-coverage on heat-cfntools at the moment, but it seems like a worthwhile thing to test for."}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-10-06 09:45:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Clint,

We can't mock this but we do test (or will shortly) in tempest and smokestack.  heat-cfntools unit test coverage is difficult to achieve - really have to focus on functional testing for most of this package."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-10-06 19:14:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Actually I'd like to avoid installing packages during functional testing due to the risk of transient errors beyond our control.

It would be very useful if we could have some unit test coverage of the package install command sequences."}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-10-07 00:36:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm not exactly clear on what the test conditions would be that would show us success.  There is no mocking for shell utilities and we don't want to install rpms in unit tests to verify the installation worked properly."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-10-07 01:15:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

On inspecting heat-cfntools' tests, its clear that we're doing lots of mocking of Popen already, so that should be trivial to extend into PackagesHandler.

I don't expect full coverage, but we should definitely have a test which fails without this change, and passes with it. I don't care so much if rpm fails when this is run in reality, just that we are calling RPM using its documented interfaces.

I have avoided pushing back on this sort of thing in the past because I felt like heat-cfntools might go the way of "compatibility monster" rather than "useful self contained tools". It seems the latter is more likely now, so lets start shepherding it into more maintainability.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-14 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]

commit_message:
Improve orchestration speed by 50%

A tabbing error in the original RPM installation code results in
multiple RPM operations run for each item in the RPM installation
list.  A small template like F19's WordPress_NoKey.yaml result in
50% speed increase by making the change.  Templates with more RPMs
could expect better results.

Change-Id: I9ee45d78a016890647a7ee0936ce2757c0859326
Closes-Bug: #1235796

More ubuntu fixes for install guide

This patch contains fixes based on testing the install guide
for ubuntu.

The following chapters have been confirmed under Ubuntu

2 Basic Operating System Configuration
3 Configuring Identity Service
4 Configuring Image Service
6. Adding a dashboard

Currently testing:
5 Configuring the Compute Services

The following sections are verified OK:
Installing the Nova Controller Services.

It cannot verify the full chapter as the networking section
does not exist.

Change-Id: I6d1f1ae7e1ef78b56be3481c5a17ebed883cb7f1

Fix incorrect flavor name issue

* Returns 400 bad request if flavor name is not specified
* or flavor name is whitespace.

Fixes bug #1202690

commit_message:
Add property port_id to RouterInterface

Since neutron router-interface-add api supports subnet_id and and
port_id so we should support it in heat resource RouterInterface.

Fixes bug #1223733

Change-Id: Ib0d7ffa3c478747a91b70beab4a78eadf7c9dfcb

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-14 00:13:48.000000000', 'message': 'Replicator:  Add Storage Policy Support

Adds awareness to the replicator for storage policies, processing
policy rings accorindingly.  Extends storage policies by adding
a type key which is required for the replicator to understand
what to do with per policy data.

Change-Id: I35deaea7c0fc660ccf432a3134837d3335ac6f75
Implements: blueprint swift-ec
'}]
commit_message:
Replicator:  Add Storage Policy Support

Adds awareness to the replicator for storage policies, processing
policy rings accorindingly.  Extends storage policies by adding
a type key which is required for the replicator to understand
what to do with per policy data.

Change-Id: I35deaea7c0fc660ccf432a3134837d3335ac6f75
Implements: blueprint swift-ec

commit_message:
Added info about enabling VT in BIOS

There are a few different key words to look for in BIOS options.
Also, even if the grep command outputs, you might still have to
enable something in BIOS.

Change-Id: I3a3b0817926d77347e0cde8f2f421ee9d80f85f2

commit_message:
added password parameter for automated install

As requested for the use with Vagrant I added an ption to Keystone.sh
so it can be called with the mysql root password as a parameter.
The interactive option is still available if the script is called
without a parameter

Cleaned up some comments and prompts

Change-Id: I754a9baba2d7b30b5105e45130f57142cb4614be

commit_message:
added support for skipping sev processing on logs

we really only support severity processing on some kinds of logs,
but we could support timestamps on many more of them. Be explicit
about what we support severity on so that we don't make logs go
away if we ask for them at DEBUG level and they don't have it.

Change-Id: I7460ccfdb4354137988257a9aed319b8dc7297a6

commit_message:
Fix datetime format in FakeCache

Since keystoneclient v0.4.0 auth_token middleware requires
the expiratin date and time of an authentication token to
be in ISO format.

This patch updates FakeCache which is used for unit tests
for ACL to generate expiration date and time according to
ISO 8601.

Closes-bug: #1238591
Change-Id: Ie6e542fe1acc7658ca62db5dfdfd949ff15c8373

commit_message:
Don't cat tempest.conf for ./stack.sh

When installing openstack, stack.sh roughly will print ~13000 lines
 for console output. We'd better not dump , which means
another several hundred lines.

Furthermore, dumping file content during openstack installation looks
a bit strange

Change-Id: I9aaca2d39406720a5574020c0e40bf0454213a26

Benchmark scenarios for Rally: Nova servers

The patch provides Rally with the basic set of Nova benchmark scenarios for
servers, including procedures of their creating/deleting and snapshotting.

Blueprint benchmark-scenarios

commit_message:
Update information for openSUSE

Based on testing the setup

Add a note that NetworkManager should not be used

Remove setence about asking for password since we pass the password
on the command line.

Change-Id: I73bde10c7df96d1502021f989da624586bb94a3f

commit_message:
Mention ceilometer service names and alarm notifier

The alarm notifier was not documented, add it.
Add to all items the name of the daemon like we do in other parts
of the getstart sections.

Change-Id: Icdd5b3588d3ea733cfc746a6d101534c4be7b777
Closes-Bug: #1238582

commit_message:
Benchmark scenarios for Rally: Nova utils

This patch contains the base class for Rally benchmark scenarios for Nova.
The class provides several helper methods for booting/suspending servers
and images. These methods will be of great use in the actual benchmark
scenarios for Nova servers, floating_ips, metadata enrties etc.

Blueprint benchmark-scenarios

Change-Id: I29301d6ee1b1cca2939004acf3d681b01f101b44

commit_message:
Easy OSTF launching based on file config

The presented patch provides several necessary lines of code that make it
possible to run the OSTF tests based on a config written in a file -the facility
which is currently needed for the Rally project. All the user has to do is to insert
an instruction like:

os.environ['CUSTOM_FUEL_CONFIG'] = 'path/to/config/file'

before the actual OSFT launch. Changing the FuelConfig() method
implementation as well as moving its call in the BaseTestCase class
into the setUpClass() method serves for this goal and ensures that
the config values will override the default ones.

Change-Id: I1e202048da33a0d7d26c704e01f60f7a682cbfa9

thats currently not what the hacking H404 check is enforcing. I'm purely fixing the hacking warning here. Do you really suggest that I should adjust the docstrings to something that isn't code-style checked?

I'm inclined to rework the existing hacking check or improving it to cover the "less than 80 chars" case, but for now I'd rather prefer to get this patch landed than no improvement at all.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-15 06:03:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Fix all occurences of H404 Hacking warning

This fixes all triggers of hacking 0.6.x's warning:
H404 - multi line docstring should start with a summary.
and enables gating check on H404.

Change-Id: I034bd1f05da3f279d8d79aa14a7f6ce8bef5047c

commit_message:
Rename get_callable_name to get_fully_qualified_name

The functionality provided by getting the callable name
is also pretty useful for getting the fully qualified name
of generic objects so lets rename it and use the same
function for both callable names and object fully qualified
names.

Change-Id: I12ce150df9dea8df4c678d4dda7a09785f885224

Sorry I didn't get to this earlier

We don't have a really well-defined feature freeze for oslo.config, but we've been saying that Nova's feature freeze proposal date is a sensible time to start deferring new Oslo features

So, I'm thinking we defer this for now ... but let me know if there's an urgent use case for this. For example, a blueprint in another project that's already approved for Havana

Regarding using oslo-incubator in oslo.config - I'd rather avoid it, but I am doing it in oslo.messaging. If it's a fairly trivial piece of code, I think I'd just copy and paste it :("}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-08-23 15:22:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Mark, sure, I am happy to wait for this to land until whenever you decide. While I was not trying to get things in before the freeze, I did think that Aug 22 was the feature proposal deadline for basically the whole project, and the patch was proposed a full day before that, so I'm not sure why this would suddenly be blocked on the basis of feature proposal freeze since it specifically is for reviews created _after_ the date. Also I had thought that oslo.config is not on the release cadence.

Anyway, zero urgent need, so please just remember this change when things are un-frozen.

As far as blueprints, this was driven by a bug fix, not a blueprint. This would make things better for Heat basically immediately. I don't see the need for a blueprint on something that can be implemented in a single patch. It is self documenting and extremely straight forward. However, if you would like a formal spec and blueprint, I am happy to write one.

The place I want to use this is here:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/43189/3/heat/common/config.py

Where the BytesOpt would simply let users have more readable config files. I specifically intend BytesOpt to be able to be dropped in where IntOpt is used without affecting backward compatibility (a bare int == a byte)."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-31 06:03:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned

commit_message:
Add a type for byte values

Provide convenient suffixes that users expect, like M for megabyte and k
for kilobyte.

Change-Id: I9cad6b9552d301cd11effb06d4fb030637d4267c

So, something else that I'm not sure also about.

The action_engine has a concept of a notifier that can be setup and used to receive updates about what is happening to a flow and tasks. I believe this can be done in celery, can the same interface be used with your engine to make it transparently work in the same manner between action_engine and distributed_engine? 

Maybe this is a later change, but it would be nice to have feature equivalence in both engines (even if one is distributed and one isn't)."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-09-25 04:40:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: (1 inline comment)

So, about that notifier for flow status stuff. Celery already has a monitoring system that hooks into that event listener (complete with UI) http://docs.celeryproject.org/en/latest/userguide/monitoring.html#flower-real-time-celery-web-monitor. Real time monitoring of each task (can see state, args passed, time it took to execute, time it executed at, what worker it ran on, etc, etc). It's a tested/maintained tool, so I figured I'd just let users use that bad boy to monitor their flows."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-09-25 06:55:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: (3 inline comments)

As for the notification using flower, this means there will be a functional difference between using distributed and not using distributed. That functional difference means things will not operate in the same manner when switching engine types. 

Is there anyway the distributed_engine can emit the same notificaitons that the action_engine would, and then it would be transparent to users of taskflow what is happening. Of course those users can also use flower, but it would be nice to have functional feature parity at the engine level without having to require people to also use flow.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-09-25 07:01:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

Flower (not flow)'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-09-25 07:07:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

Also flower is more for monitoring, notifications that are emitted at the engine level i would suspect will be used for more things than monitoring, like triggering other functions and such. Flower is nice for monitoring/tracking, but I think we should aim towards having the same notifications coming out of both engines (and at the same places). 

Otherwise they aren't really transparently compatabile engines, they are 2 different engines with different results (and different notifications) and different interfaces. It becomes sorta impossible to switch one engine out for another if they don't produce the same kind of outputs, notifications and results (how they work internally can be different of course).

This is especially important if people while building there flows in say (nova, cinder) actually depend on those notifications to be recieved to do follow-up activities. Telling them to go use flower wouldn't work for that kind of usage."}, {'account_id': 7359, 'date': '2013-09-25 07:39:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-25 07:40:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13: Doesn't seem to work

So a few concerns still.

Most of the code-related comments I think can be fixed.

But there is still one big concern that I don't know how it will be addressed (we have talked about it on IRC). None of the unit tests actually run the engine, so if we don't have a pretty clear plan as to how we will test the engine (without manually doing it) then there is no way to know if a change elsewhere in taskflow will break the distributed_engine running. That makes it hard to know if distributed_engine is working at any point in time, or if its broken.

I don't know if this is solvable, since setting up celery likely isn't something that jenkins can do (but maybe it can) but it would be really nice if we had some solution that didn't involve commenting out the engine.run() method."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-10-05 21:27:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19: (1 inline comment)

Python3 changed the behavior of dict.keys such that it is now
returns a dict_keys object, which is iterable but not indeable.
You can get the python2 result back with an explicit call to list.

Refactor list(*.keys()) so that it just uses list().

commit_message:
python3: Refactor dict for python2/python3 compat

Python3 changed the behavior of dict.keys such that it is now
returns a dict_keys object, which is iterable but not indexable.
You can get the python2 result back with an explicit call to list.

Refactor list(*.keys()) so that it just uses list().

Change-Id: Ib2e9646ac967e9bd7cc4f47e2099f5d1358808a9
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

'}, {'created': '2013-10-12 04:20:42.000000000', 'message': "VMware: Fixed upload-to-image for available volume

Cinder generally does not allow upload-to-image operation on a volume
that is 'in-use'. This can however be over-ridden using the '--force True'
flag. The VMware driver cannot support upload-to-image when the volume is
in-use. This is a restriction for the VMware driver alone. When the user forces
an upload on a volume that is 'in-use' the Cinder api layer sets the volume

commit_message:
VMware: Fixed upload-to-image for available volume

Cinder generally does not allow upload-to-image operation on a volume
that is 'in-use'. This can however be over-ridden using the '--force True'
flag. The VMware driver cannot support upload-to-image when the volume is
in-use. This is a restriction for the VMware driver alone. When the user forces
an upload on a volume that is 'in-use' the Cinder api layer sets the volume
status to 'uploading' and calls into the driver code to upload. In this
scenario the VMware driver needs to fail the operation.

The current driver code here does this check wrongly by looking for volume
status of 'in-use'. Fixing this check to identify an in-use volume correctly.

Fixes bug: 1237338

Change-Id: If54edfdc242a7a1bff442b6bb4c5a9865eede1dc

commit_message:
Fix a typo of tabstop

Only in nova/compute/manager.py, there is 'tabstop=6'. This change was
introduced at commit:2d0578c5. But this is an unintentional change.
This commit fix it to the same as others.

Change-Id: I5c4ffe354e2d37caa231de561ac257f23c6ab7d5

[{'created': '2013-10-11 02:53:40.000000000', 'message': "py33: _print func failed in MultiThreadingManager

The MultiThreadingManager._print() can not work well, then
print_stream / error_stream get nothing.

1. Use six.print_() to keep compatability between Python 2 & 3.

2. In Python 3, all text is unicode, and str.encode() returns bytes.
   str.encode = encode(...)
      S.encode(encoding='utf-8', errors='strict') -> bytes

   So, bypass the encode while in PY3.

Close-Bug #1238359

Change-Id: Ibae89a02ca59c7c0657f1c7c79b13a11b6f7d6a4
"}]
commit_message:
py33: _print func failed in MultiThreadingManager

The MultiThreadingManager._print() can not work well, then
print_stream / error_stream get nothing.

1. Use six.print_() to keep compatability between Python 2 & 3.

2. In Python 3, all text is unicode, and str.encode() returns bytes.
   str.encode = encode(...)
      S.encode(encoding='utf-8', errors='strict') -> bytes

   So, bypass the encode while in PY3.

Close-Bug #1238359

Change-Id: Ibae89a02ca59c7c0657f1c7c79b13a11b6f7d6a4

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-10 01:59:46.000000000', 'message': "py33: objet of type 'map' has no len()

In Python 2:
map(function, sequence[, sequence, ...]) -> list

In Python 3:
map(func, *iterables) --> map object

In Python 3, map() returns an iterator, it has no len().
Transform it to list with list().

Close-Bug #1237719

Change-Id: I1bd13c778f84a8f209be21753f153cd995e76a9c
"}]
commit_message:
py33: objet of type 'map' has no len()

In Python 2:
map(function, sequence[, sequence, ...]) -> list

In Python 3:
map(func, *iterables) --> map object

In Python 3, map() returns an iterator, it has no len().
Transform it to list with list().

Close-Bug #1237719

commit_message:
py33: use six.next() to get the next item of iterator

six.next(it):
Get the next item of iterator 'it'. StopIteration is raised if the iterator is
exhausted. This is a replacement for calling it.next() in Python 2 and next(it)
in Python 3.

Close-Bug #1237680

Change-Id: I3c4d2c75f86a168c4ddfe3572af160271d2048ec

[{'created': '2013-10-09 12:12:51.000000000', 'message': "py33: strings are unicode by default in Python 3

Python 2:
str.encode = encode(...)
   S.encode([encoding[,errors]]) -> object

Python 3:
str.encode = encode(...)
   S.encode(encoding='utf-8', errors='strict') -> bytes

In Python 3, strings are always Unicode. value.encode() will return
b'xxx', it can not match string 'xxx'. So, bypass the encoding in
Python 3 env.

Close-Bug #1237309

Change-Id: Ic5f69bc25b07a9999eb01022caee1f1c26f8df74
"}]
commit_message:
py33: strings are unicode by default in Python 3

Python 2:
str.encode = encode(...)
   S.encode([encoding[,errors]]) -> object

Python 3:
str.encode = encode(...)
   S.encode(encoding='utf-8', errors='strict') -> bytes

In Python 3, strings are always Unicode. value.encode() will return
b'xxx', it can not match string 'xxx'. So, bypass the encoding in
Python 3 env.

Close-Bug #1237309

Change-Id: Ic5f69bc25b07a9999eb01022caee1f1c26f8df74

commit_message:
Update log message for add_host_to_aggregate

When add host to aggregates with availability zone, if the host
is already in one availability zone, then the host cannot be added
to another availability zone.

When user do above operation, nova api will report error message,
but the error message does not include blank space between
<availability zone> and zone name, also the error message include
two periods.

The fix was adding blank space and removes one period for the message.

Change-Id: I7307288be194d3ce6de05b77433bbe2626ae46d9
Closes-bug: #1237303

commit_message:
py33: module compatibility issues

Six provides simple utilities for wrapping over differences between
Python 2 and Python 3. It is intended to support codebases that work
on both Python 2 and 3 without modification.

Make use of six to resolve the module compatibility issues.
Then the other type of compatibility issues will be exposed.

Close-Bug #1236811

Change-Id: I4a66ea617666ae88515436e3399c65a6d2ae7c29

commit_message:
NetApp check for 7 mode controller version

Queries the filer api version and raises error
if the version is unsupported.

Closes-Bug:#1223474

Conflicts:

	cinder/tests/test_netapp.py
	cinder/tests/test_netapp_nfs.py
	cinder/volume/drivers/netapp/iscsi.py
	cinder/volume/drivers/netapp/nfs.py

Change-Id: I430a41d63a2541891fdbdb20dacab9f69fa44291
(cherry picked from commit 1af8f46ea1c8e2a33ca554fa6ef3262d055c54ed)

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-07 08:28:01.000000000', 'message': 'doc: disable intersphinx mapping

The intersphinx extensions let one reserve a link namespace and map it
to a remote URL, for example to refer to the Python documentation. A
drawback is that, from time to time, Sphinx will attempt to download an
object inventory from the remote, that is not convenient when running
sphinx in offline mode such as in a plane.

I am assuming most projects will not link to upstream Python
documentation and hence it is safe to remove the intersphinx extension.
The lines are left commented to let one easily reenable the feature
whenever they have a use case of it.

Change-Id: Idef8e88545715a3f1cb9ace002960a7ad3e37b69
'}]
commit_message:
doc: disable intersphinx mapping

The intersphinx extensions let one reserve a link namespace and map it
to a remote URL, for example to refer to the Python documentation. A
drawback is that, from time to time, Sphinx will attempt to download an
object inventory from the remote, that is not convenient when running
sphinx in offline mode such as in a plane.

I am assuming most projects will not link to upstream Python
documentation and hence it is safe to remove the intersphinx extension.
The lines are left commented to let one easily reenable the feature
whenever they have a use case of it.

Change-Id: Idef8e88545715a3f1cb9ace002960a7ad3e37b69

commit_message:
Change alarm_history.detail to text type

The existing alarm_history.detail column size is 255 chars,
which is not enough for some large JSON payloads.

Change to Text column to make sure we store all detail.

Closes-Bug: #1236861
Signed-off-by: Stephen Gran <stephen.gran@guardian.co.uk>
(cherry picked from commit 57eb9e904aacae166d7265a914960415c57cd133)

Change-Id: I1460c2a5bbd5cb465a605bb80775853468148026

Previously when an admin created a combination alarm on
behalf of an non-admin identity, this had the effect of leaking
visibility onto alarms that would not normally
be visible to the non-admin tenant.

Now we validate all alarm ids with the project ID of the non-admin
identity that will ultimately own the alarm instead of the project ID
of the API caller.

Change-Id: I5d1cf41c9182f09bc37b93deb14dda58f1d6dcd6

commit_message:
Avoid leaking admin-ness into combination alarms

Previously when an admin created a combination alarm on
behalf of an non-admin identity, this had the effect of leaking
visibility onto alarms that would not normally
be visible to the non-admin tenant.

Now we validate all alarm ids with the project ID of the non-admin
identity that will ultimately own the alarm instead of the project ID
of the API caller.

Fixes bug #1237632

Change-Id: I5d1cf41c9182f09bc37b93deb14dda58f1d6dcd6
(cherry picked from commit a8e93ddc9e0d79c603573a2e0f26cef115579534)

commit_message:
create the TEMPEST_STATE_PATH

the new test id issolation in devstack-gate broke stable/grizzly
because state dir didn't exist. Instead of the work around in
devstack-gate, just backport directory creation to devstack
stable/grizzly

Change-Id: I822b5572e058864fd11a2dacbf1d8d709075e73d

commit_message:
Change resource.resource_metadata to text type

The existing resource.resource_metadata column size is 5k chars,
which is not enough for some large JSON metadata payload,
so change to as Text column to make sure store all JSON string
without truncating.

Fixes bug #1220683

(cherry picked from commit 7f3e7cea0ec9d8eb7095c2790fe0ba327c2df242)

Change-Id: I898ff2706cbaccafec6060bbdb0bbf68a4209edd

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-11 21:07:40.000000000', 'message': 'Avoid leaking admin-ness into threshold-oriented alarms

Fixes bug 1237567

Previously when an admin created a threshold-oriented alarm on
behalf of an non-admin identity, this had the effect of leaking
visibility onto statistics for resources that would not normally
be visible to the non-admin tenant.

Now we ensure that an additional implicit threshold rule query
constraint is added on the project ID of the non-admin indentity
that will ultimately own the alarm.

This is acheived by splitting the query validation from the
construction of the kwargs from the query. The addition of the
implicit query constraint to the threshold rule can then be
delayed to a later point in the dispatch path where the full
context of the alarm is known (so that we can check for the case
where the alarm is created by an admin on behalf of another tenant).

Change-Id: I1adae8c899112e7c3eb4e94f3f68262c84a98574
(cherry picked from commit 7ee6f6d29451be4f2c9d5146e4cfbc147f33ee04)

commit_message:
Avoid leaking admin-ness into threshold-oriented alarms

Fixes bug 1237567

Previously when an admin created a threshold-oriented alarm on
behalf of an non-admin identity, this had the effect of leaking
visibility onto statistics for resources that would not normally
be visible to the non-admin tenant.

Now we ensure that an additional implicit threshold rule query
constraint is added on the project ID of the non-admin indentity
that will ultimately own the alarm.

This is acheived by splitting the query validation from the
construction of the kwargs from the query. The addition of the
implicit query constraint to the threshold rule can then be
delayed to a later point in the dispatch path where the full
context of the alarm is known (so that we can check for the case
where the alarm is created by an admin on behalf of another tenant).

Change-Id: I1adae8c899112e7c3eb4e94f3f68262c84a98574
(cherry picked from commit 7ee6f6d29451be4f2c9d5146e4cfbc147f33ee04)

Fix heat deletion failed if floating ip is not found

Novaclient will throw out a Not Found exception if the
floating ip not exists. Heat should catch this exception
to continue to delete the stack.

Closes-Bug: #1234593

The maximum hostname on Linux is 64 characters.  DHCP is limited to
this host maximum.  Unfortunately Nova allows the creation of servers
with names > 63 characters in length.  This patch is a short-term
solution to improve the failure condition, so we draw attention to
the problem, enabling the user to work around with shorter names.
A subsequent patch will be required which mangles names such that we
truncate or compact names automatically.

'}]
commit_message:
Raise error if instances are created with names > 63 chars

The maximum hostname on Linux is 64 characters.  DHCP is limited to
this host maximum.  Unfortunately Nova allows the creation of servers
with names > 63 characters in length.  This patch is a short-term
solution to improve the failure condition, so we draw attention to
the problem, enabling the user to work around with shorter names.
A subsequent patch will be required which mangles names such that we
truncate or compact names automatically.

Closes-Bug: 1238272
Change-Id: I2114135b7f4b649a906c3adaea1869d1a1290a3b

commit_message:
Return Integer or Float casted value in NumberParam

Integer value used in parameter, so failed validation in properties.
The solution here is return Integer casted value or Float casted value
as value of NumberParam.

The method of which type choose for cast is same of Property.str_to_num.

Fixes bug #1226494

Change-Id: I9f7d894ffae8a728dce783d5881af3d377268b93

production environments, but it breaks plugins without per-tenant
quota extension. In these plugin quotas tables is not loaded.

commit_message:
Fallback to Quota Conf Driver if Quotas table is not defined

commit de15e0b9c5 enabled Quota DB driver default considering
production environments, but it breaks plugins without per-tenant
quota extension. In these plugin quotas tables is not loaded.

This commit fallbacks to ConfDriver if Quota model is not loaded by
checking neutron.db.quota_db which defines Quota model is imported.

Change-Id: Idaaaa9810598cfd3e5ce70020f498643b4819d16
Closes-Bug: #1236993
(cherry picked from commit 46495f4995b6604cb249b688aaa249ef4e8b18ef)

commit_message:
Use L3 api from vpn ipsec driver via service plugin

VPNaaS and ML2 plugin won't work, because ML2 plugin
supports service version of L3.
In this commit, we modify ipsec driver to use L3 plugin.
This is also backward compatible change, because if L2 plugin
supports L3 get_service_plugin API returns L2 plugin.

Fixes bug 1238846

Change-Id: I36e541bb2e3e1df2e01f73a74f3e9005af6c38b7
Note: Exsiting unit test covers this change
(cherry picked from commit 8eb573528551d4a74c146c9d171505f7d472bb6a)

[{'created': '2013-10-11 21:25:56.000000000', 'message': "Fix auto-deletion of ports when deleting subnets in ML2

When a subnet is deleted, certain ports referencing it are
auto-deleted. The implementation of NeutronDBPluginV2.delete_subnet()
does this at the DB level, so ML2's mechanism drivers were not being
called.

Ml2Plugin.delete_subnet() is changed to not use the base class's
method, and to auto-delete ports by calling its own delete_port()
method outside of the transaction. A loop avoids race conditions with
ports being asynchronously added to the subnet.

The logic in Ml2Plugin.delete_network() is also fixed to properly
handle auto-deleting ports and subnets, and debug logging is added to
the various delete methods.

Closes-Bug: 1234195
Partial-Bug: 1235486
Change-Id: I6d74f89d39ea8afe6915f1d2f9afdf66c0076f5a
(cherry picked from commit ed78b563e13f1ed9189d7c4b9cd4317f2a50e734)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix auto-deletion of ports when deleting subnets in ML2

When a subnet is deleted, certain ports referencing it are
auto-deleted. The implementation of NeutronDBPluginV2.delete_subnet()
does this at the DB level, so ML2's mechanism drivers were not being
called.

Ml2Plugin.delete_subnet() is changed to not use the base class's
method, and to auto-delete ports by calling its own delete_port()
method outside of the transaction. A loop avoids race conditions with
ports being asynchronously added to the subnet.

The logic in Ml2Plugin.delete_network() is also fixed to properly
handle auto-deleting ports and subnets, and debug logging is added to
the various delete methods.

Closes-Bug: 1234195
Partial-Bug: 1235486
Change-Id: I6d74f89d39ea8afe6915f1d2f9afdf66c0076f5a
(cherry picked from commit ed78b563e13f1ed9189d7c4b9cd4317f2a50e734)

commit_message:
Improve default logging configuration

By default, a number of serious exceptions were not being
logged. Adding a logger for 'django'-related logs resolves this.

Also:
 - Add loggers for missing clients and django_openstack_auth
 - Add a default level for individual loggers (what makes it out to
   the log file remains determined by the handler configuration)

Change-Id: Id3478ac8ec79f22c19ef66e747f3701f98a36611
Closes-Bug: #1236423
(cherry picked from commit 3ccd927251a69905b2c3f1ee496c174eaeb1f8eb)

[{'created': '2013-10-11 19:12:09.000000000', 'message': "Add support for keystoneclient 0.4.0

Keystoneclient auth_middleware changed the way it parses the datetime
returned from the cache, breaking the Ceilometer unit tests. This patch
fixes the fake cache system that's used in unit test, so it works with
all keystoneclient versions.

This also update the sample configuration files to include the new
options provided by keystoneclient 0.4.0.

Fixes-Bug: #1238529

Change-Id: Iecfd50d9e9801aeb919f2c09a728e4ea15245a5e
(cherry picked from commit e3cef871ac5a92d38d42fe09d9ac2dbe4404f679)
"}]
commit_message:
Add support for keystoneclient 0.4.0

Keystoneclient auth_middleware changed the way it parses the datetime
returned from the cache, breaking the Ceilometer unit tests. This patch
fixes the fake cache system that's used in unit test, so it works with
all keystoneclient versions.

This also update the sample configuration files to include the new
options provided by keystoneclient 0.4.0.

Fixes-Bug: #1238529

Change-Id: Iecfd50d9e9801aeb919f2c09a728e4ea15245a5e
(cherry picked from commit e3cef871ac5a92d38d42fe09d9ac2dbe4404f679)

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-08 00:56:44.000000000', 'message': "Allow env registry paths to be relative to env file

The default base_url is now derived from the location
of the environment file, so now resource registry paths
can be relative instead of absolute URLs.

This change also includes the following:
* more complete test coverage
* refactor of _process_environment_and_files and
  _get_file_contents to make test coverage easier
* use the full URL instead of just the file name in the
  'files' field to avoid key clashes
* make _get_file_contents less specific to the resource registry
  so it can be used for other inclusion tasks
* stop calling _get_file_contents recursively so that deep URLs
  do not get loaded, instead call _get_file_contents on
  resource_registry and resource_registry.resources.*
Closes-Bug: #1233912

Change-Id: Ic729cbcd1711b89e91daf0d645f4f56bae2accf3
"}]
commit_message:
Allow env registry paths to be relative to env file

The default base_url is now derived from the location
of the environment file, so now resource registry paths
can be relative instead of absolute URLs.

This change also includes the following:
* more complete test coverage
* refactor of _process_environment_and_files and
  _get_file_contents to make test coverage easier
* use the full URL instead of just the file name in the
  'files' field to avoid key clashes
* make _get_file_contents less specific to the resource registry
  so it can be used for other inclusion tasks
* stop calling _get_file_contents recursively so that deep URLs
  do not get loaded, instead call _get_file_contents on
  resource_registry and resource_registry.resources.*
Closes-Bug: #1233912

Change-Id: Ic729cbcd1711b89e91daf0d645f4f56bae2accf3

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-09 04:21:44.000000000', 'message': "Increase heat's default max_template_size

devstack has a small 10k max template size.  This is too small for
many templates that may be used during development.  Thus, we need
to change this and devstack to a larger value.

Change-Id: I474c7cbc196a4e94ba67cab4e2ca2263dc902e26
"}]
commit_message:
Increase heat's default max_template_size

devstack has a small 10k max template size.  This is too small for
many templates that may be used during development.  Thus, we need
to change this and devstack to a larger value.

Change-Id: I474c7cbc196a4e94ba67cab4e2ca2263dc902e26

commit_message:
Replace DBError with DeletionFailed for DataSource and Job

Foreign key constraints on DataSource and Job objects by JobExecutions
cause DBError exceptions if those objects are deleted while they are
referenced by a JobExecution.  Replace the DBerror with a SavannaException
so that the REST api reports the error nicely.

Change-Id: I756f561b019895c8c2c39f17bd3a05da31ad6440
Closes-Bug: #1235229

commit_message:
Remove the 2.0 related version code

Since the HDP 2.0 merge will not make the 0.3 cutoff we're removing
the code for it's integration.  In addition, some issues with the
dashboard are observed when the 2.0 skeleton code is in place.

fixes:  bug #1235258

Change-Id: Id037982977d269ec75161c08cdda2995ac3ac674

commit_message:
Add job parameters and arguments configuration

 * Appearance config, params and/or args sections
 depending on job type:
   MR   - only configs
   Pig  - configs, params, args
   Hive - configs, params

Fixes Bug #1228138

Change-Id: Ida66111bc9148adf7cb4a6667e214b12dc40aced

commit_message:
Make a note about Object deepcopy helper

This adds some clarifying documentation on the NovaObject.__deepcopy__
helper.

Change-Id: I0d2e997a6826537c059e34fcfc8b894662d42ee3

commit_message:
Avoid caching quota.QUOTAS in Quotas object

This removes the local caching of the QUOTAS module in the Quotas
object. If we ever use deepcopy() on objects, this will cause
us trouble. Since it's not necessary, remove it for now.

Change-Id: I0d0e5fba9cd26c1648ff724238554478e65f62ea

subject: Remove transitional callable field interface

commit_message:
Migrate NovaPersistentObject and ObjectListBase to Fields

This actually uncovers an invalid testing scenario we had for lists,
which was using non-objects in the list-of-objects tests.

Related to blueprint structured-object-fields

Change-Id: I94609c1fd4a8b011e71bde7d9510ec2d3cb29868

subject: Migrate Instance object to Fields

commit_message:
Update to latest tox config

tox 1.6 ensures that we get pip 1.4 which we need to be able to filter
unwanted pre-releases. We also have to configure tox to not give 1.4 the
--pre option, since we want the change in behavior. Addtionally, we want
to run setup.py develop inside of the venv, rather than running sdist
outside of the venv, to avoid dependency sequencing issues.

Change-Id: I2e3284f86712c040eb98df2df4723daf4472a519

commit_message:
Support namespaces in vArmour L3 Agent

- create/remove virtural router objects when namespaces is enabled

- When L3 agent restarts, remove all configuration we created

Closes-Bug: #1222968
Change-Id: I742e4a8e69e8935259077aeb6be9cda5f3c2fb78

commit_message:
Helper function to delete extra dhcp options

Simply adds a helper function to delete extra dhcp
options associated with a port. Can be utilized
to update extra dhcp options associated with a
port.

Fixes: bug #1228391

commit_message:
Plug Vif into Midonet using Neutron port binding

Currently Midokura uses its own script (mm-ctl) to bind ports. However, support
for using this script is left out of the nova and neutron projects. This causes
confusion and makes deployments unnecessarily complicated for customers using
Havana. This fix is to change nova to properly use mm-ctl. Corresponding
changes will be submitted to devstack and neutron.

Change-Id: I64779dc6b34b963b78c98f8654b7c201a48905e6
Closes-Bug: 1235132
