commit_message:
Add port bindings to ports created in Midonet

Currently Midokura uses its own script (mm-ctl) to bind ports. However, support
for using this script is left out of the nova and neutron projects. This causes
confusion and makes deployments unnecessarily complicated for customers using
Havana. This fix is to change Neutron to properly set up port bindings to use
the "midonet" vif driver when creating a port. Corresponding changes will be
submitted to the devstack and Nova projects.

Closes-Bug: 1235134
Change-Id: Ifdc826492316370a2acc70655c6afbf7940e133c

commit_message:
Heat require ceilometerclient 1.0.6

Currently stack-update with a ceilometer alarm fail.

Ceilometer API require to put the full alarm json on update.

To partially update a alarm like heat does we needs
ceilometerclient>=1.0.6, to include this:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48402/

Fixes bug #1229162

Change-Id: Ie580198865ea068ae7e23be43dc1fec6efc3c0e9

commit_message:
Make admin token request optional

Introduce a new config option "authn_method" to specify the method
to be used to request the authentication (i.e. admin) token. "authn_method"
can be either "password" or "external". Setting it to "external" effectively
disables admin token request as it signifies admin token is to be facilitated
via external means (i.e. 2-way SSL).

Note that "authn_method" is optional and default to "password". This is a
backward compatible change. Also, this mechanism can be expanded in the future
to support pluggable authentication.

DocImpact
Fixed bug 1228309

Change-Id: I7a1d40819fc5700faee8d6e2fa624b2adca23934

messages:
[{'account_id': 330, 'date': '2013-09-25 17:20:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This seems weird to me, and perhaps not the best way to implement it.

Can you provide more details on the use case in which Swift is deficient right now? It seems that the problem you are solving is a cache-invalidation issue. Who is the "we" in the commit message. If it's "Swift", then no the stored hash is not a cache. The stored hash is vital in detecting certain classes of errors (and is validated when it is initially written).

This patch means that data will be read off the disk twice (once to recalculate the header, once to serve). An alternate implementation could be done in middleware where if the trigger header is detected, the response would be a multipart response where the 2nd part is the recalculated hash. (Yes that requires a client to know that the response is multipart, but you're already changing the client to send new headers...)

Keeping this as a "No score" review since I'd like more information.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-25 17:27:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Doesn't seem to work

Build failed.  For information on how to proceed, see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GerritJenkinsGit#Test_Failures

- gate-tempest-devstack-vm-large-ops http://logs.openstack.org/03/48303/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-large-ops/55f96f7 : SUCCESS in 12m 10s (non-voting)

"}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-09-25 17:32:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Can you describe the work the object server would do on a HEAD request with an X-Etag-Nonce header to a 5 gigabyte object compared to the work the client would do?  Can you describe how the goal of validating data integrity would be different in this case from a client performing a full GET on the object and validating that the checksum of the resulting data stream is equal to the Etag sent in the header (similar to what the diskfile close/verify method already does and will invoke quarantine if the data is invalid; the auditor also does this)?

If this change is pursued, the commit message should include DocImpact."}, {'account_id': 693, 'date': '2013-09-25 17:38:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

For data archives like the Library of Congress who are interested in using Swift, their use-case requires provable guarantees around end-to-end data integrity that cannot be shown in Swift currently. If data is silently corrupted, the user won't know about it until they try to download it. Since the time-horizons of this use-case are typically a lot longer than we (the OpenStack community) are used to dealing with, that's not a viable solution because the object in question may not exist EXCEPT in Swift.

The "we" in the commit message is swift. While the metadata is a valuable internal data structure for handling corruption, the fact that we return metadata from that structure instead of recalculating makes it a cache.

This patch does not modify the metadata of the object as it exists on disk. It merely makes it possible for an end-user to optionally prove that swift isn't lying about the integrity of uploaded objects. I can also modify it to only recalculate on HEAD requests, so it avoids the double-read.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-09-26 04:36:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Interesting; so this would pick one of the object's replicas at random*, then force an immediate verification of the checksum instead of waiting for the auditors?

That's interesting, though I wonder about the utility of doing it on a GET request, as the client is going to retrieve the entire object anyway, so it can just verify the checksum in the usual fashion.

(I'm also undecided about the desirability of this... seems like a good way to DoS a cluster with a craptillion recalculate-etag requests on big-ass objects. Although, even if it doesn't make the cut for "lives in Swift git repository",  that does not preclude one from writing this as an object-server middleware.)

* blah blah read affinity blah blah timing blah'}, {'account_id': 1009, 'date': '2013-09-26 18:11:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

"ameliorated"?  I had to look that up.  = )'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2013-09-28 21:53:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It's an interesting idea, especially using the nonce to prove you recalculate the hash.

On the other hand:
1) This could also be implemented as middleware (either proxy or object server)
2) What you are validating is that no corruption has happened between the last audit pass and the current request. And ignoring that the etag can be validated by the client and refetched if necessary (which would need to happen anyway to prove no network corruption).

So yeah, I can see it as a really nice feature in a client or in an archival-specific deployment. "It could be done externally" isn't good enough on its own to prevent inclusion into Swift, but it's usefulness (or lack of harm) for a more general use case would need to be shown too. As well as the set of core devs being favorable to maintaining the code from here on out.'}, {'account_id': 860, 'date': '2013-10-03 10:10:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Another argument for the do-it-in-middleware approach is that you can make this apply to large (DLO/SLO) objects.

A different approach is to add a header that's kind of the opposite of x-newest e.g., x-consensus. The proxy would get the metadata of all three replicas and compare them. If they differ, it would pick the two replicas that agree their value of ETag and use one of them to handle the GET operation.

(I'm using three replicas as an example -- you probably use quorum_size() as part of this).

If all three differ, the request fails. I suspect the auditor/replicator won't fix up the object in this scenario, so the object is probably lost anyway.

Note: x-consensus does not cause the server to actually re-calculate the ETag so there is no extra overhead at the server side. The client must calculate the ETag of the downloaded data, but it should be doing that anyway."}, {'account_id': 693, 'date': '2013-10-03 23:07:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I see the value in making this middleware as it's really optional and not every implementation of swift requires the feature. It also needs to be modified so that X-RECALCULATE only happens for HEAD requests. However, the other suggestions X-CONSENSUS or forcing the end-user to recalculate after downloading the objects in question fail in this case because there is no guarantee that the user who is downloading the object is the user who uploaded it and therefore cannot be certain that the object has not been silently modified in situ.

Assuming there is a path for inclusion of the middleware in swift, I'm happy to rewrite it as a piece of optional middleware. However, I do not have a lot of free time so I do not have any desire to commit to maintaining a patch. 

I was asked to speak about the feasibility of using OpenStack to these individuals, and I had to tell them honestly that Swift was not ready. It seems to me that this set of users with very large and interesting storage deployments would be a pretty awesome for OpenStack, and next year I'd like to be able to say that the open source community listened to their needs."}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2013-10-05 01:00:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

My attempt at a threaded discussion here:

<quote>
I see the value in making this middleware as it's really optional and not every implementation of swift requires the feature. It also needs to be modified so that X-RECALCULATE only happens for HEAD requests. However, the other suggestions X-CONSENSUS or forcing the end-user to recalculate after downloading the objects in question fail in this case because there is no guarantee that the user who is downloading the object is the user who uploaded it and therefore cannot be certain that the object has not been silently modified in situ.
</quote>

The end user can confirm that the md5 (sent "first" in the headers) matches the contents of the body of the response. This ensures that the object was transmitted unmodified from Swift to the client (hand wavey level of "guarantee"--it protects against network issues, not necessarily malicious MITM. It's a checksum.).

This is something the client should probably do anyway, and it will catch any bit-rot errors if they are transmitted before the swift audit process finds it.

<quote>
Assuming there is a path for inclusion of the middleware in swift, I'm happy to rewrite it as a piece of optional middleware. However, I do not have a lot of free time so I do not have any desire to commit to maintaining a patch.
I was asked to speak about the feasibility of using OpenStack to these individuals, and I had to tell them honestly that Swift was not ready. It seems to me that this set of users with very large and interesting storage deployments would be a pretty awesome for OpenStack, and next year I'd like to be able to say that the open source community listened to their needs.
</quote>

First, I think it is very possible to be included into swift with some sort of feature flag (ie deployers need a way to not allow it since it could cause issues in some cases).

We all are very busy, but one of the fantastic parts of Swift is there is a whole community maintaining the project. While your individual participate is valued, nobody would expect you to maintain your patch forever. The whole community maintains the project. This, in fact, is why we have code reviews and multiple core reviewers must approve something before it's merged. I know you know all of this, but I want to be explicit about that here.

Finally, please don't advocate your patches with threats future bad PR. Your patch will be accepted or not based on its technical merits, the use case it solves, and the approval of the rest of the Swift community.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-12 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-12 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-25 17:00:30.000000000', 'message': "Optionally recalculate object ETag on GET or HEAD.

For certain categories of use-case, the way we handle object checksums
does not suffice to prove data integrity of the objects. Since we cache
the checksums in the object's metadata, the data can be silently
corrupted when the end-user tries to validate it. This silent corruption
can be ameliorated if we allow the end-user to explicitly request that
the response recalculate the hash, and we can prove we're not cheating
if we allow them to specify a nonce that we prepend to the hash
calculation.

This commit adds two optional headers to the object server's get or
head requests:

    X-Recalculate-Etag: When set, causes the object-server to
                        recalculate the ETAg before returning it to the
                        end user.
    X-Etag-Nonce: A string which is prepended to the etag recalculation.
                  When set, it implicitly acts as though
                  X-Recalculate-Etag is also set. This header has a
                  MAXIMUM length of 128 bytes. Setting this header to
                  longer than 128 Bytes raises an HTTPPreconditionFailed
                  exception.

Change-Id: I99096abe720b00a6bec4efb438aef8915877b129
"}]
commit_message:
Optionally recalculate object ETag on GET or HEAD.

For certain categories of use-case, the way we handle object checksums
does not suffice to prove data integrity of the objects. Since we cache
the checksums in the object's metadata, the data can be silently
corrupted when the end-user tries to validate it. This silent corruption
can be ameliorated if we allow the end-user to explicitly request that
the response recalculate the hash, and we can prove we're not cheating
if we allow them to specify a nonce that we prepend to the hash
calculation.

This commit adds two optional headers to the object server's get or
head requests:

    X-Recalculate-Etag: When set, causes the object-server to
                        recalculate the ETAg before returning it to the
                        end user.
    X-Etag-Nonce: A string which is prepended to the etag recalculation.
                  When set, it implicitly acts as though
                  X-Recalculate-Etag is also set. This header has a
                  MAXIMUM length of 128 bytes. Setting this header to
                  longer than 128 Bytes raises an HTTPPreconditionFailed
                  exception.

Change-Id: I99096abe720b00a6bec4efb438aef8915877b129

commit_message:
Adds support for the os-list-scheduler-hints extension

The Nova API for instance creation supports a scheduler_hints mechanism
whereby the user can pass additional placement related information
into the Nova scheduler.

The os-list-scheduler-hints API extension makes the list of supported
hints available to users by querying each of the configured scheduler
filters

Related Nova change: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/34291/

Implements blueprint scheduler-hints-api

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ib5111da0545d226e303d499e51ccff2a48b64e44

server as default route until we kill file injection, may not be the
default route, so we need to be able to influence routing.

Change-Id: I698682183a301141e224e5713a49b23f8e6c863e

commit_message:
Handle setting a new default route.

In a production environment, the overcloud, which has it's metadata
server as default route until we kill file injection, may not be the
default route, so we need to be able to influence routing.

Change-Id: I698682183a301141e224e5713a49b23f8e6c863e

'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2013-08-26 16:36:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

This is going to slow devstack-gate runs down because the package won't be cached like all the other debs.

The nodepool setup scripts (previously in devstack-gate, soon to be removed) are in the openstack-infra/config repository in ./modules/openstack_project/files/nodepool/scripts/

They are used to cache things that devstack uses, such as debs and images for our gate runs.  It's actually possible that merging this might even break those setup scripts if the package name is different than what's in the normal ubuntu archive (I haven't checked).  At any rate, it would be good to add the archive in those image setup scripts so that it can cache the correct deb.

Finally, I wonder if this should check to see if the archive is already in place and short-circuit the keyserver and apt_update if it is."}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-08-29 02:28:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

commit_message:
[WIP] Adds a new table TaskInfo

- move 'input', 'message' and 'result' columns to table 'task_info'
-introduce new domain object SparseTask
-introduce 'run_at' column to the 'tasks' table
-introduce TaskRepo(proxy.Repo) and SparseTaskRepo(proxy.Repo).
-seperate out soft delete columns to 'SoftDeleteMixin' from 'ModelBase'
-introduce GlanceBase(SoftDeleteMixin, ModelBase). Have it extended by respective model entities.

partly implements bp async-glance-workers

Change-Id: I6d918cb44d474ca0f0d2dc06364903c7f43844e4

commit_message:
Don't change the default attach-method

Don't change the default attach-method.  The one configured by the
libguestfs packager is supposed to be correct for all libguestfs
users, and making ad hoc changes to it is not advisable.

For more information, see:
https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=984409#c8

Fixes bug: 1220102
Change-Id: Ie7726c37dd579e2c95b6156a9ddfdff9e855af83

commit_message:
Utilizes assertNotIn

Using assertTrue and the 'not in' operator to test
if an element is in a sequence is too python2.4.
Our unit testing framework supports assertNotIn,
which was created for these types of tests.

This patch is a mere sed replace of one-liner assertTrue and assertFalses

grep -lR "assert.* in " nova/tests/* | \
xargs sed -ri 's/(\W+self.assert)True(.+) not in (.+)(\)$)/\1NotIn\2, \3\4/'

grep -lR "assert.* in " nova/tests/* | \
xargs sed -ri 's/(\W+self.assert)False(.+) in (.+)(\)$)/\1NotIn\2, \3\4/'

Change-Id: I99471c81b0cbcd46bb48aca8570f3234f2924f60

commit_message:
Fixes UnicodeEncodeError for keystone action with non-English characters

When processing keystone tenant-delete action with non-English
characters, will result in UnicodeEncodeError, so should encode text.

Fixes bug #1237892

commit_message:
Use L3 api from vpn ipsec driver via service plugin

VPNaaS and ML2 plugin won't work, because ML2 plugin
supports service version of L3.
In this commit, we modify ipsec driver to use L3 plugin.
This is also backward compatible change, because if L2 plugin
supports L3 get_service_plugin API returns L2 plugin.

Fixes bug 1238846

Change-Id: I36e541bb2e3e1df2e01f73a74f3e9005af6c38b7
Note: Exsiting unit test covers this change

commit_message:
Replace assertEquals with assertEqual - multiline

The method assertEquals has been deprecated since python 2.7.
http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html#deprecated-aliases

Also in Python 3, a deprecated warning is raised when using assertEquals
therefore we should use assertEqual instead.

Additional assertEqual related indent fixes were done also.

This is part of blueprint assertequal

Change-Id: I4283e021b4a66c91291b7011a20a3d93d97148c4

commit_message:
Libvirt: disallow live-mig for volume-backed with local disk

This patch makes libvirt raise an error if a live migration was
requested without shared storage for a volume-backed instance, if that
instance has any local disks.

The reason is that without shared storage, local disks will be
re-created on the destination node which can result in loss of data.

Change-Id: Ic96dabf6020e957309280862b325792faf44b1f5
Closes-bug: 1236356
(cherry picked from commit cf89e78a1b921adee5b1943600315b0637fdefdc)

commit_message:
Fixes error on live-migration of volume-backed vm

Live-migrating a volume-backed vm (i.e. booted from volume)
is currently broken.

This patch fixes the case where a volume-backed vm is to be
live-migrated without shared storage on compute nodes or
ephemeral volumes attached to the instance. Specifically, it
stops create_images_and_backing() from blowing up when no disk
info is supplied.

Change-Id: Icec7a6e7225ebe029e24d3be303c9ab01818f30e
Fixes: bug 1235182
(cherry picked from commit 0cbb231cd14c8cb767b67d89b14d0ef46b3e8018)

commit_message:
Speed up the process of reboot a paused VM for KVM

When reboot a paused VM without hard option on KVM, the
KVM libvirt driver failed to soft reboot the VM, then after
wait 120s, libvirt driver try to hard reboot the process and
finally succeed.

For a paused VM instance on KVM, libvirt driver should hard
reboot it directly.

Change-Id: Id6f002e55410441ee7fa8cd2bab558e268eeb77b
Closes-Bug: #1238435

commit_message:
Add variable to expand for format string

Also, add a space to separate words.

Otherwise, you can get a warning message similar to this:

2013-10-03 19:45:48.086 12123 WARNING 186_new_bdm_format [-] Got an unexpected block device %sthat cannot be converted to v2 format

Change-Id: I7f32e9d93d524a0763918d636f43bd7d2638b5de

commit_message:
Fix DeprecationWarning when printing exception

On Python 2.6, this results in an error like:
/usr/lib/python2.6/site-packages/cinderclient/shell.py:524:
DeprecationWarning: BaseException.message has been deprecated as of
Python 2.6
  message = e.message

Should use the method from novaclient commit 8c4e145b92, which
works well with python2 and python3.

Change-Id: Ifbd78ad158ae87670bdee4e247469091efaa3260

commit_message:
Remove obsolete redhat-eventlet.patch

See I62ce43a330d7ae94eda4c7498782a655e63747fa for the gorey details on
why this exists.

As of this fix:

  https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/pull/34

which was released in eventlet 0.13, we no longer need the patch.

This has now been removed from oslo-incubator, so this is really just
syncing that removal.

commit_message:
Fallback to Quota Conf Driver if Quotas table is not defined

commit de15e0b9c5 enabled Quota DB driver default considering
production environments, but it breaks plugins without per-tenant
quota extension. In these plugin quotas tables is not loaded.

This commit fallbacks to ConfDriver if Quota model is not loaded by
checking neutron.db.quota_db which defines Quota model is imported.

Change-Id: Idaaaa9810598cfd3e5ce70020f498643b4819d16
Closes-Bug: #1236993

commit_message:
Avoid leaking admin-ness into combination alarms

Previously when an admin created a combination alarm on
behalf of an non-admin identity, this had the effect of leaking
visibility onto alarms that would not normally
be visible to the non-admin tenant.

Now we validate all alarm ids with the project ID of the non-admin
identity that will ultimately own the alarm instead of the project ID
of the API caller.

Fixes bug #1237632

Change-Id: I5d1cf41c9182f09bc37b93deb14dda58f1d6dcd6

commit_message:
Use Unix style LF instead of DOS style CRLF

This was causing pyflakes to fail with syntax errors on some systems:
<stdin>:22: invalid syntax

Change-Id: I57669392a5ee2a786d2a6e18a9dfd0abb054b71b

commit_message:
xeanpi: pass network_info to generate_configdrive

Currently network_info is being fetched when generating config drive.
This change ensures the network_info that is already available is
re-used when generating the config_drive.

In addition, it is more consistent to use the network_info that is
passed into this function, rather than potentially lazy loading the
whole info_cache of the instance from the DB, which may not yet be
populated when we are generating the metadata for ConfigDrive anyway.

Fixes bug 1224508
Change-Id: I3e6f5a987593ecd422be61ac50c0d74463ba25d5

commit_message:
mute useless console output, when run ./stack.sh

Run ./stack.sh will dump ~400 lines of information, because of
tar xvfz pip-*.tar.gz, and python setup.py install.

We'd better mute stdout for the two steps, to make console cleaner

Change-Id: Icf87947e020acb48d8cbe4cdcc1641f060e50f6d

commit_message:
Change alarm_history.detail to text type

The existing alarm_history.detail column size is 255 chars,
which is not enough for some large JSON payloads.

Change to Text column to make sure we store all detail.

Change-Id: I1b4ebee33954acc1f41a4cf0d0b991055b7d4fe9
Closes-Bug: #1236861
Signed-off-by: Stephen Gran <stephen.gran@guardian.co.uk>

commit_message:
Xenapi: set hostname when performing a network reset

The hostname is removed from the metadata on Xen to address an
issue where windows instances get renamed on reboot.  This
becomes a problem when a network reset is called for instances
using the agent communication mechanism.  In that case the
agent will incorrectly rename the host.  Thus the
hostname needs to be set prior and cleared after a network reset.

The setting of the metadata params also need to be atomic so
locking was added that matches to the locking provided by
other data (network metadata).

Fixes bug 1236877

Change-Id: I021fae5bff2c4213a433672fc3920c836237176f

commit_message:
A resource to generate random strings

A common pattern for templates is to define parameters
for passwords and specify the password on stack create.
For complex templates this can impact template maintainability
and makes stack creation more complicated.

In addition, a password parameter leaves the temptation of
using the same password (or worse, the parameter default) on
each stack launch which raises the security risk.

This resource allows secrets to be generated in the template and
propagated to compute resources as needed. Often the user will
never want to see the generated string, but if they do they
can put it in a stack output.

This resource has been requested by the tripleo project
who run trunk heat, so it will be of immediate benefit to them.

Implements blueprint random-string-resource

Change-Id: I044fc7717133fc7a3520dca774300024925ff2aa

I don't think this a good solution to this bug. The issue here is that we allow volume backed migrations without shared storage (imho not a valid thing to do - I will explain) and this blows up in libvirt drivers's pre_live_migration method which attempts to de-serialize a None in _create_image_and_backing.

The real bug here is that we allow non-shared-storage live migration with volume backed instances - the reason we should disallow this is that only because the root disk is a volume, it does not mean it doesn't have additional (e.g. ephemeral disks) that need shared storage to be migrated.

I will raise a bug for this, since just creating all the disks empty on the destination which is not shared, and then migrating over (which is what this patch will allow) seems like a scenario we need to disable."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2013-10-07 11:08:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

"}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-10-07 11:15:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Nikola,

Thanks for looking at this. I agree that this is not a perfect solution and was hoping that those more versed with live migration would chime in.

The first problem here is that it does not appear to be clear what we want to allow/disallow for live-migration. IMO the case of allowing a volume-backed vm to live-migrate and have its ephemeral disks copied over is valid. Could you explain why this should not be allowed?

The second issue, is that libvirt.driver._create_images_and_backing() does not check if disk_info_json is None before processing it.'}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-10-07 11:18:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

(2 inline comments)

I have filed https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1074054 and we should be fixing that instead.

I have reported bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1236356 whcih should have all explanations needed, but to answer your questions
>The first problem here is that it does not appear to be clear what we want to allow/disallow for live-migration. IMO the case of allowing a volume-backed vm to live-migrate and have its ephemeral disks copied over is valid. Could you explain why this should not be allowed?

It will not have it's epehemeral disks copied over, it will have them created empty. there will be no VIR_MIGRATE_NON_SHARED_INC flag set when doing a call to virDomainMigrate as this flag is only set if block_migration is passed. I think this is an invalid situation.

> The second issue, is that libvirt.driver._create_images_and_backing() does not check if disk_info_json is None before processing it.

_create_images_and_backing should be more robust, but that is a separate issue.

I am -2ing this. We should be fixing the real bug instead. Would appreciate a second look though - so I will look for another core person and remove the -2 if there is doubt."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-10-07 13:38:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Please disregard the sentence "I have filed https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1074054 and we should be fixing that instead." in the previous message.'}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-10-07 14:57:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

Nikola,

Your principle objection here is that the ephemeral disks are not properly copied over which is fair enough. Is there a reason why we could not silently force block migrate for any local ephemeral disks?

Non-local ephemeral volume support was recently added to nova libvirt (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/36042/24) so we would want to allow users to take advantage of having network attached ephemeral disks when doing a live migrate wihtout having to have shared storage and do a full block copy.'}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-10-07 15:19:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> Is there a reason why we could not silently force block migrate for any local ephemeral disks?

You could try - but in libvirt this would mean you have to block migrate all the disks - which means including the volume. This won't work as expected with the current code and is likely the exact opposite of what we want to do. Hence my suggestion to make it a non-starter unless there is *only* the cinder volume.

> Non-local ephemeral volume support was recently added to nova libvirt (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/36042/24) so we would want to allow users to take advantage of having network attached ephemeral disks when doing a live migrate wihtout having to have shared storage and do a full block copy.

I am not sure how the RBD image backend works in detail - so I will review it now and add further comments. 

But even if it is possible to have the 'local' disks 'attached' on more than one node with RBD - imagebackend API is not meant for these kind of operations, and will fail for other image backends.

Making this work smoothly still seems like a non-trivial patch work, and in the general case - the bug is still valid."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-10-07 15:55:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Looking at the Rbd back-end code in virt.libvirt.nova.imagebackend it seems I was correct - the Image class simply does not provide a way to do what we need (it can only import a downloaded image).

I am not sure I like the idea of changing that, but even if we are going to - this needs a blueprint with approval and cannot be masked as a bug fix.

I still think disabling live mig w/o shared storage unless there are absolutely no local disks is what we want to do here.'}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-10-07 16:16:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Nikola,

I agree. I think there are already motions to get that sorted out so lets see what happen, hopefully it will be properly discussed at the summit. I will see if I can get something suitable done for this patch so that we can at least get it working in some sense. Thanks for your comments!'}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-10-10 19:02:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-10 19:54:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

commit_message:
Fixes error on live-migration of volume-backed vm

Live-migrating a volume-backed vm (i.e. booted from volume)
is currently broken.

This patch fixes the case where a volume-backed vm is to be
live-migrated without shared storage on compute nodes or
ephemeral volumes attached to the instance. Specifically, it
stops create_images_and_backing() from blowing up when no disk
info is supplied.

Change-Id: Icec7a6e7225ebe029e24d3be303c9ab01818f30e
Fixes: bug 1235182

commit_message:
Add keystoneclient CredentialsManager if missing

The keystone v3 client doesn't include the 'ec2' manager, even
though the EC2 API is included in the default pipeline.

This commit creates the ec2 manager manually if it's missing
(and necessary). It uses the same call that the client itself
should have used.

Change-Id: I83e7bfa04cde5093c10bf2bc27af5ec03da4b48e
Closes-bug: #1236326
(cherry picked from commit 7187d12a1727b98e91c7d90941de6bd46f098809)

commit_message:
capping python-troveclient version

Verson 1.0 of python-troveclient is not backwards compatible with
the trove work in Horizon. There are too many places to fix the
compatibility issues for Havana, so for now pinning the release
version.

Closes-bug: #1238121

Change-Id: If0ec929180e083aa47bdb688879ba2f63fdcd2a3
(cherry picked from commit b49b952be096c4d50228b5ca0dc40ad19e0211a6)

commit_message:
Remove obsolete redhat-eventlet.patch

See I62ce43a330d7ae94eda4c7498782a655e63747fa for the gorey details on
why this exists.

As of this fix:

  https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/pull/34

which was released in eventlet 0.13, we no longer need the patch.

This has now been removed from oslo-incubator, so this is really just
syncing that removal.

Change-Id: I84267f3c6726cb2e750f615e107c48b12c6ed353

commit_message:
Libvirt: disallow live-mig for volume-backed with local disk

This patch makes libvirt raise an error if a live migration was
requested without shared storage for a volume-backed instance, if that
instance has any local disks.

The reason is that without shared storage, local disks will be
re-created on the destination node which can result in loss of data.

Change-Id: Ic96dabf6020e957309280862b325792faf44b1f5
Closes-bug: 1236356

commit_message:
Fix nova DB 215 migration script logic error

This addresses a minor (albeit important) logic error in the migration script
for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46379/ - that script currently deletes
compute node stats for active compute nodes.  This patch reverses that logic
so it deletes the correct set of compute node stats.

Also included is a migration test case to demonstrate the behavior.

Change-Id: I77afcf443357d0767ac933d791a565289eabee9a
Closes-Bug: #1238281
(cherry picked from commit c3330931113ac2edf5961a653e5c2cfe459c13a0)

commit_message:
Script to filter logs for ERRORs based on whitelist

The script will take a directory or url containing log files.
For now all non-whitelisted errors will be dumped to the console but
the script will always return success. Once we are convinced it is reliable
enough we can change it to fail on non-whitelisted errors.

Partially implements blueprint fail-gate-on-log-errors

Change-Id: I30b0eee1055f47aaad7984d886c739ccf5aa6186

commit_message:
xenapi: simplify PV vs HVM selection logic

The logic to inspect a disk to determine if an image is PV or HVM has
been removed. This change follows on from that simplification.

As before, if I user wants to use PV mode, or HVM mode, then can set
vm_mode=xen or vm_mode=hvm, respectively. This will override any other
way of selecting the mode.

For consistency, we now check the os_type to be either windows or linux,
which, without vm_mode, chooses HVM or XEN mode respectively.

For backwards compatibility, all VHD and DISK type images default to
vm_mode=xen.

In all other cases, we default to HVM, as this is the safest option
that works with most images.

Fixes bug 1206828
DocImpact
Change-Id: Iab2ffdc7ad396b853c7aed20d46bf12320b76c21

commit_message:
emit warning while running flake8 without virtual env

run_tests.sh -N -p

It will call the flake8 installed on your host to detect PEP8, and
the flake8 plugin "OpenStack hacking" may not installed on your
host, so this command may not detect the OpenStack Style Commandment
supplied by hacking(e.g H202).

run_tests.sh -p
it will call the flake8 from virtual env, flake8 plugin "OpenStack
hacking" installed in virtual env will be triggered.

The result from "run_tests.sh -p" should be trusted, and jenkins uses
virtual env to run flake8 too.

When "-N" is enabled, check whether hacking can be imported, if not,
emit warning to stderr to remind user.

Test method
-----------
Suppose hacking is not installed on your host

$ ./run_tests.sh -p
no warning

$ ./run_tests.sh -p -N
emit warning

$ source .venv/bin/activate
$ ./run_tests.sh -p
no warning

$ ./run_tests.sh -p -N
no warning

Close-Bug #1215400

Change-Id: If5125c180a3ebea72dc1fb96817523a6e07b2d66

commit_message:
Raise error if instances are created with names > 63 chars

The maximum hostname on Linux is 64 characters.  DHCP is limited to
this host maximum.  Unfortunately Nova allows the creation of servers
with names > 63 characters in length.  This patch is a short-term
solution to improve the failure condition, so we draw attention to
the problem, enabling the user to work around with shorter names.
A subsequent patch will be required which mangles names such that we
truncate or compact names automatically.

Closes-Bug: 1238272
Change-Id: I2114135b7f4b649a906c3adaea1869d1a1290a3b

commit_message:
Do not pass unicode where byte strings are wanted

Some versions of the tarfile module break when unicode data is
passed as metadata (like the version). See
http://bugs.python.org/issue11638 for details.

This change ensures that version number is always a byte strings
under python 2, where the problem exists.

Change-Id: Ic266cd7cce0394d28794ee61afe269f1296be2a2

Do we even need to do this now?  pwtools isn't actually being used in Oslo anywhere, so the requirement should just be added to the OpenStack projects that need this functionality."}, {'account_id': 6162, 'date': '2013-10-11 21:09:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

The idea was to have a common library to generate passwords.  Password generation is done in Nova and in Trove.  At the moment Trove just uses a GUID which we would like to change to something more secure.

We could just use this library in Trove if there is no interest in having it in oslo.  Any thoughts on this?'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-10-11 21:16:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

But pwtools _is_ that common library, isn't it?  What would be put in Oslo?  Once the requirements change merges Trove can use pwtools directly as far as I can tell."}, {'account_id': 6162, 'date': '2013-10-11 21:20:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

I thought I needed to update the oslo requirements and oslo common.
Is that not correct?  I can totally abandon this if it's not needed.

Thanks in advanced for the clarification :)"}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-10-11 21:26:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Nope, to use pwtools all you need as a prereq is https://review.openstack.org/#/c/51068/ .  Once that merges you can add pwtools to Trove's requirements and start using it right away.  Oslo would only be involved if you wanted to put a wrapper around pwtools or something, but it sounds like that's not the case."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-10-11 21:29:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

That's right, if nothing in oslo will call the new library then it does not need to be in the requirements for oslo. After the master requirements list is updated, the same entry will need to be added to the projects that do want to use it (I think the infra team has a bot that creates the changeset automatically now, but it has to be reviewed by hand)."}, {'account_id': 6162, 'date': '2013-10-11 21:32:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Abandoned

All we need is this sucker.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/51068/'}]

Remove whitespace from cfg options

This extra whitespace will cause warnings in the openstack-manuals,
thus remove it.

It looks like postgres does not like the 'select for update' on the specific sql query that gets generated...we might have reached an impasse...looking..."}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-10-09 03:31:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I've been looking into this locking, and am starting to get convinced that SQL requires that "FOR UPDATE" locks the rows that are returned by the query from further updates or deletion, but does not necessarily prevent new rows from being inserted that a subsequent issue of the same query would return. If that is the case, using with_lockmode('update') in these queries would not prevent new ports or subnets from being created. Maybe we need to explicitly lock the tables instead. The same issue may apply in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46563/ and https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48774/. Any ideas?'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-10-10 03:52:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-10-10 04:01:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

This version removes the with_lockmode('update') calls that were added to the queries in the previous version. This locking is not compatible with outer joins in PostgreSQL, and even when supported, does not prevent new rows from being added to the database concurrently, which was their primary intended purpose. Therefore delete_network() or delete_subnet() may return an exception when something that should be auto-deleted is added concurrently, but no corruption or deadlock should result."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-10 04:46:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Works for me

commit_message:
Fix auto-deletion of ports when deleting subnets in ML2

When a subnet is deleted, certain ports referencing it are
auto-deleted. The implementation of NeutronDBPluginV2.delete_subnet()
does this at the DB level, so ML2's mechanism drivers were not being
called.

Ml2Plugin.delete_subnet() is changed to not use the base class's
method, and to auto-delete ports by calling its own delete_port()
method outside of the transaction. A loop avoids race conditions with
ports being asynchronously added to the subnet.

The logic in Ml2Plugin.delete_network() is also fixed to properly
handle auto-deleting ports and subnets, and debug logging is added to
the various delete methods.

Closes-Bug: 1234195
Partial-Bug: 1235486
Change-Id: I6d74f89d39ea8afe6915f1d2f9afdf66c0076f5a

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-09 18:36:59.000000000', 'message': 'Avoid leaking admin-ness into threshold-oriented alarms

Fixes bug 1237567

Previously when an admin created a threshold-oriented alarm on behalf of
an non-admin user, this had the effect of leaking visibility onto statistics
for resources that would not normally be visible to the non-admin user.

Now we ensure an additional implicit threshold rule query constraint is added
on the project of the non-admin user who will ultimately own the alarm.

Change-Id: I1adae8c899112e7c3eb4e94f3f68262c84a98574
'}, {'created': '2013-10-09 19:28:24.000000000', 'message': 'Avoid leaking admin-ness into threshold-oriented alarms

Fixes bug 1237567

Previously when an admin created a threshold-oriented alarm on
behalf of an non-admin identity, this had the effect of leaking
visibility onto statistics for resources that would not normally
be visible to the non-admin tenant.

Now we ensure that an additional implicit threshold rule query
constraint is added on the project ID of the non-admin indentity
that will ultimately own the alarm.

This is acheived by splitting the query validation from the
construction of the kwargs from the query. The addition of the
implicit query constraint to the threshold rule can then be
delayed to a later point in the dispatch path where the full
context of the alarm is known (so that we can check for the case
where the alarm is created by an admin on behalf of another tenant).

Change-Id: I1adae8c899112e7c3eb4e94f3f68262c84a98574
'}, {'created': '2013-10-10 14:59:43.000000000', 'message': 'Avoid leaking admin-ness into threshold-oriented alarms

Fixes bug 1237567

Previously when an admin created a threshold-oriented alarm on
behalf of an non-admin identity, this had the effect of leaking
visibility onto statistics for resources that would not normally
be visible to the non-admin tenant.

Now we ensure that an additional implicit threshold rule query
constraint is added on the project ID of the non-admin indentity
that will ultimately own the alarm.

This is acheived by splitting the query validation from the
construction of the kwargs from the query. The addition of the
implicit query constraint to the threshold rule can then be
delayed to a later point in the dispatch path where the full

commit_message:
Avoid leaking admin-ness into threshold-oriented alarms

Fixes bug 1237567

Previously when an admin created a threshold-oriented alarm on
behalf of an non-admin identity, this had the effect of leaking
visibility onto statistics for resources that would not normally
be visible to the non-admin tenant.

Now we ensure that an additional implicit threshold rule query
constraint is added on the project ID of the non-admin indentity
that will ultimately own the alarm.

This is acheived by splitting the query validation from the
construction of the kwargs from the query. The addition of the
implicit query constraint to the threshold rule can then be
delayed to a later point in the dispatch path where the full
context of the alarm is known (so that we can check for the case
where the alarm is created by an admin on behalf of another tenant).

Change-Id: I1adae8c899112e7c3eb4e94f3f68262c84a98574

commit_message:
Correct arch substitution for undercloud template.

Updates toci_test.sh so that we put the correct bare metal
arch into the heat template. This fixes deployment issues
when trying to deploy an x86_64 overcloud.

Change-Id: I45413082f08c8827f4aa43f994d62d8bfbd6e4bb

commit_message:
Allow customising the floating range.

The floating range for a cloud is tied to the network environment it's
deployed into - like the network config, it needs to be customisable.

Change-Id: Ie656cb2ceb6dabcc03120301b50bd7b7777b90d6

commit_message:
Customize the power_manager for the undercloud.

If TOCI_PM_DRIVER is set then we inject it into the undercloud
template.

This allows people to use non-standard power management settings
via TOCI using our default heat templates. Even though you can
choose undercloud-vm.yaml for virtual power management and
undercloud-bm.yaml for IPMI the ability to set this within TOCI
is still desirable since there are other drivers in use as well.

Change-Id: I903c86ad9b11ab6de0b289c3d575749609aedc0b

I never looked at that patchset.

It's not enough as it won't correct people who have already ran past migration 203. So you still need to fix it for them (hence a new migration+tests) but as far as I can see no data will be lost so we don't need a backup table.

I also feel like this is a unique case where you are modifying an old migration instead of just fixing it in a new one. This means that the state of the system can be different on downgrade from your migration. For example, if I had ran 203 already and then went from 215 -> 216 back to -> 215 I would expect it to be the same as when I started (at 215). However in this case if I go back to 215 I will still have the proper column length rather than the truncated one just as people who run 203 after this patch won't have the wrong version.

I hope that makes sense :-)"}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2013-09-26 13:13:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: (5 inline comments)

The truncation recovery code looks good to me; I think if someone has created a new resource that that code doesn't handle, they'll either have already figured it out or will when this is mergedthough I do suggest an email communication about this fix.

However, I disagree with using the placeholder migration 217.  If this were against the release candidate, using 217 is appropriate; however, this one is against trunk, so should not be using one of the placeholders.  Make sure the new migration is idempotent and make this one use a non-placeholder migration, and then when proposing it for merge into the release candidate, use the placeholder.

(This is how I believe migrations are to work in this case; you can check with Russell to see if my understanding is correct and correct me if I'm wrong.)"}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2013-10-09 05:51:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

Thanks for your comments, Joshua, Kevin,

I agree with you for not using the placeholder migration 217, I will change it.

So the remaining point is "whom does this migration help?"

 Most users:
   * do initial installation with Havana release.
   * need only the fixing of 203_make_user_quotas_key_and_value.py.
 Some users:
   * update their OpenStack environments with master repository.
   * need the fixing of 203_make_user_quotas_key_and_value.py.
   * need truncation recovery code of 217_fix_project_user_quotas_resource_length.py.
 A few users:
   * update their OpenStack environments with master repository, and add some customesized quotas. (injected_file_content_bytes_by_cell, etc)
   * need the fixing of 203_make_user_quotas_key_and_value.py.
   * do not need truncation recovery code of 217_fix_project_user_quotas_resource_length.py.

To be honesty, I also am in "Most users".
So I don't have strong opinion between "Some users" and "A few users".'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2013-10-09 06:38:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 19.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-09 07:18:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19: Works for me

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-19 01:05:20.000000000', 'message': 'Fix "resource" length in project_user_quotas table

"nova quota-update --injected-file-content-bytes 1024 --user <user> <tenant>"
is executed, the result is like the following:

$ nova quota-update --injected-file-content-bytes 1024 --user [..]
ERROR: The resource could not be found. (HTTP 404)
$

This is due to invalid length of resource in project_user_quotas table.
Current length is 25 and "injected_file_content_bytes" is shortened to
"injected_file_content_byt":

mysql> select resource, hard_limit from project_user_quotas;
+---------------------------+------------+
| resource                  | hard_limit |
+---------------------------+------------+
| injected_file_content_byt |        100 |
+---------------------------+------------+

The length of resource in quotas table, which is used for each tenant
quota, is 255. So the one of project_user_quotas should be 255.

Fixes bug #1227434

Change-Id: I3e080c30698dde62625eb477a85e1816191ff1e5

commit_message:
Fix "resource" length in project_user_quotas table

"nova quota-update --injected-file-content-bytes 1024 --user <user> <tenant>"
is executed, the result is like the following:

$ nova quota-update --injected-file-content-bytes 1024 --user [..]
ERROR: The resource could not be found. (HTTP 404)
$

This is due to invalid length of resource in project_user_quotas table.
Current length is 25 and "injected_file_content_bytes" is shortened to
"injected_file_content_byt":

mysql> select resource from project_user_quotas;
+---------------------------+
| resource                  |
+---------------------------+
| injected_file_content_byt |
+---------------------------+

The resource of project_user_quotas table has been changed to invalid
length(25) since I56ad98d3702f53fe8cfa94093fea89074f7a5e90. The change
does not seem intention, that would be just a bug.
This patch fixes the problem.

Closes-Bug: 1227434

Change-Id: I3e080c30698dde62625eb477a85e1816191ff1e5

commit_message:
Create a better exception in Fn::Replace

if the replace value is the wrong type we get a generic exception
out of string.replace that does not really help with debugging
a template.

Change-Id: I2d6d5509b8900b11bfbf148230d57438e1f9962a

commit_message:
Catch the appropriate exception for missing instance

Catch ClientException instead of NotFound since this is
what the underlying client library actually throws.

Closes-Bug: #1236911
Change-Id: I1e7f3c69c216d19705cab9bdcd7302e1b917fdd4

commit_message:
Return Integer or Float casted value in NumberParam

Integer value used in parameter, so failed validation in properties.
The solution here is return Integer casted value or Float casted value
as value of NumberParam.

The method of which type choose for cast is same of Property.str_to_num.

Fixes bug #1226494

Change-Id: I9f7d894ffae8a728dce783d5881af3d377268b93

commit_message:
Add an element installing tuskar API service

This should make it easier to deploy tuskar in the undercloud
(basically, one will just add 'tuskar' the the list of elements
when building a disk image for the undercloud node).

This depends on Ib66e688bd7500f03dea7d4282607cd51078e9a51 to be
merged into tripleo-heat-templates to work properly.

Change-Id: I1d16e535ae50a06a8792e1613bb6b6c4647bf128

commit_message:
Remove \r chars from dhcp-all-interfaces

For some reason we are adding CR's to/etc/network/interfaces, but it
does not require them. They are a bit annoying to see in an editor and
serve no known purpose there.

Change-Id: I9aeeff5533f418f09fcf33edd42e5d85cd486d23

commit_message:
Make dhcp-all-interfaces block all interfaces

Previously dhcp-all-interfaces was only blocking the first network
interface to come up. We add an instance stanza to make it run one
instance of generate-interfaces-file per interface. We then use flock to
serialize runs of generate-interfaces-file.

Fixes bug #1233577

Change-Id: Ib16bed6b37ce0789e315ef57e05ac561470a6f2a

commit_message:
Fix ifquery call in dhcp-all-interfaces

Ifquery does not print anything for interfaces which only have a single
iface line. It does, however, return non-zero if the interface is not
configured at all, so we can use that to indicate whether or not there
is a configuration.

Fixes bug #1233579

Change-Id: Ia2fdafbea57e806eba99ae8ddaf395ebdcc306e1

[{'created': '2013-10-11 18:03:12.000000000', 'message': "Enable dhcp-all-interfaces.

While we don't need this for VM's, it's needed for real hardware
where we cannot predict the network configuration of the machines
unless we want statically configured network rules in the images
or crufty manual configuration.

This is compatible with file injection - it just tries to ensure
all undefined interfaces have a configuration stanza.

We don't have an implementation yet for RPM based machines, but
they have a workaround via their netboot configuration so at
least for machines with an eth0 will be no worse off with this
enabled - and disabling file injection is a key step for scalability.

Change-Id: Ic3c48cd9c151276b7bd9771e21065dc48b114978
"}]
commit_message:
Enable dhcp-all-interfaces.

While we don't need this for VM's, it's needed for real hardware
where we cannot predict the network configuration of the machines
unless we want statically configured network rules in the images
or crufty manual configuration.

This is compatible with file injection - it just tries to ensure
all undefined interfaces have a configuration stanza.

We don't have an implementation yet for RPM based machines, but
they have a workaround via their netboot configuration so at
least for machines with an eth0 will be no worse off with this
enabled - and disabling file injection is a key step for scalability.

Change-Id: Ic3c48cd9c151276b7bd9771e21065dc48b114978

commit_message:
Support configuring a VLAN on the public network.

The CD overcloud needs a VLAN on the neutron network node, or we can't
get public traffic to VM's in or out. This isn't an entirely general
solution but that is something we should be looking to Neutron and DHCP for,
not manual metadata: as a stop gap this should be sufficient.

Change-Id: Ifaed03b96de12453bcf23cdcf2e91bb4dc32349c

commit_message:
Add a mini-cinder volume create with resumption

Add a toy example showing how resumption works
in a miniaturized cinder like case. It allows
for the user of the example to kill the program
and later resume by providing back the initial
tracking id (think fedex/ups).

Change-Id: I7084ae50cf994e43b48c31bd22d60d77c78d50af

commit_message:
Update resource stacks automatically

When moving resources between stacks during an update, update the
resource's stack pointer automatically when adding it to its new stack.

Change-Id: I92666589fe417f5d905104d5a0890650da70e825

commit_message:
xenapi: Resize operations could be faster

 * Improves the code by using only one time resize2fs during the resize.
 * Removes the not used method: "_get_min_sectors".
 * Uses a VDI clone instead of copy in resize_disk's method.
 * Review of some test cases to accept the new behavior
   without _get_min_sectors.

Closes-Bug: 1221332
Change-Id: I40a1d7d467353ba904689d128de7f89d785b4052

commit_message:
Fixes port status hanging to build status

ML2 plugin changes the port status to "build" when get_device_details
is called. For this reason, the port status must be updated once the
port details are processed.

Fixes bug: #1224991

Change-Id: I2c0321073cc07e1764fedbfbecbc844557ac6bc9
(cherry picked from commit 01194b356e39e3b0affca67015efb7634bf28697)

commit_message:
Add __init__.py file to enable edp validation tests

Unit tests for edp validation were not running because
the absence of __init__.py in the edp directory caused
edp to not be detected as a package by tox.

Change-Id: Ief2a1a1c230a32d2c2ed99b85cbd43f852b64f4e

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-11 17:16:34.000000000', 'message': 'Fix the _assert_types test to allow for fields that are enums

Fields marked with "type: string, enum: [choices]" in JSON schemas
fail the _assert_types test because the error message is different.
When an enum field is type checked against an int, the message
becomes "<int> is not one [choices]".  This change checks for a
different message when an enum is specified.

Change-Id: I11f4f652e1522e06180d1cf537f148fd18403975
'}]
commit_message:
Fix the _assert_types test to allow for fields that are enums

Fields marked with "type: string, enum: [choices]" in JSON schemas
fail the _assert_types test because the error message is different.
When an enum field is type checked against an int, the message
becomes "<int> is not one [choices]".  This change checks for a
different message when an enum is specified.

Change-Id: I11f4f652e1522e06180d1cf537f148fd18403975

This should be enough to allow install-dependencies to run successfully
on recent versions of openSUSE, and has been tested on openSUSE 12.3.
It will not work for SLES due to the way the path to the
Cloud:OpenStack:Master repo is constructed, but it should be enough to
go on with for now.

Change-Id: I5b5485e644aa55ee96c835560a6b01869968136a
'}]
commit_message:
Support openSUSE in install-dependencies

This should be enough to allow install-dependencies to run successfully
on recent versions of openSUSE, and has been tested on openSUSE 12.3.
It will not work for SLES due to the way the path to the
Cloud:OpenStack:Master repo is constructed, but it should be enough to
go on with for now.

Change-Id: I5b5485e644aa55ee96c835560a6b01869968136a

VPN service template

Adds template example for VPN service components.

created network.

This addresses a minor (albeit important) logic error in the migration script
for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46379/; that script currently deletes
compute node stats for active compute nodes.  This patch reverses that logic
so it deletes the correct set of compute node stats.

Change-Id: I77afcf443357d0767ac933d791a565289eabee9a
Closes-Bug: #1238281

commit_message:
Fix nova DB 215 migration script logic error

This addresses a minor (albeit important) logic error in the migration script
for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46379/ - that script currently deletes
compute node stats for active compute nodes.  This patch reverses that logic
so it deletes the correct set of compute node stats.

Also included is a migration test case to demonstrate the behavior.

Change-Id: I77afcf443357d0767ac933d791a565289eabee9a
Closes-Bug: #1238281

commit_message:
Fix heat deletion failed if floating ip is not found

Novaclient will throw out a Not Found exception if the
floating ip not exists. Heat should catch this exception
to continue to delete the stack.

Closes-Bug: #1234593

Change-Id: Ifd9d34de37cc5dd57804787d8b1455f0321fc86f

commit_message:
Libvirt: allow more than one boot device

This patch makes use of the boot_index information of block devices to
allow libvirt to boot from devices other than disks, and have more than
one boot device.

It does so by calculating the boot devices based on block devices type
and boot index, and then assigning the correct list to the GuestConfig's
os_boot_dev (that was made into a list in
I38abe9edaa8f93469d58ad81a466f68c2c0d24d6).

Closes-bug: 1229327
Change-Id: Ic33894cb818ee7c44579e6d00f273b40f669aa9b

commit_message:
Add support for keystoneclient 0.4.0

Keystoneclient auth_middleware changed the way it parses the datetime
returned from the cache, breaking the Ceilometer unit tests. This patch
fixes the fake cache system that's used in unit test, so it works with
all keystoneclient versions.

This also update the sample configuration files to include the new
options provided by keystoneclient 0.4.0.

Fixes-Bug: #1238529

Change-Id: Iecfd50d9e9801aeb919f2c09a728e4ea15245a5e

commit_message:
fix: proxy mongodb storage fields overspecified

It's unnecessary to specify all the fields that should be returned by
a mongodb query, because by default, it will return all the
fields. This patch makes it so that only the '_id' field is mentioned
specifically, and that's because we don't want it leaking into the
transport layer.

Change-Id: Ib59e551b0c85f2972de86baeaa2c7e65738a9a47
Closes-Bug: 1230390

commit_message:
Remove customize dashboard section from Install Guide

This section is included already in both Cloud Admin and Config
Reference, let us reference it there instead of adding it here.

The customization is a nice to have but really optional, so a link
to another guide is fine.

Change-Id: I632e3b8d7bb6dd86ea66455bfa5bc325bd203c06

commit_message:
Cleanups for Install Guide

The purpose of this patch is to host minor cleanups for the
recently added install guide content.

Feedback to address includes:

* Ensuring ubuntu;debian is used in the most appropriate way
* determining the appropriate prompt (# vs $ vs sudo) is used

So far this patch does not address these, but it was necessary
to move the conversation away from an already merged patch :)

[{'created': '2013-10-11 09:58:21.000000000', 'message': "Setup CD overcloud public routing.

The CD overcloud requires non-devtest-default networking setup. The
tripleo-cd element needs to be able to control this: this patch seems
like a reasonable balance between JFDI and maintainable, at least for
now. In particular, the cd-tripleo element will own the config, so
it's not hidden outside of VCS and thus only-accessible-by-root.

Change-Id: Iea774b1b04d9d2d0fc159d39ef50592012caedef
"}]
commit_message:
Setup CD overcloud public routing.

The CD overcloud requires non-devtest-default networking setup. The
tripleo-cd element needs to be able to control this: this patch seems
like a reasonable balance between JFDI and maintainable, at least for
now. In particular, the cd-tripleo element will own the config, so
it's not hidden outside of VCS and thus only-accessible-by-root.

Change-Id: Iea774b1b04d9d2d0fc159d39ef50592012caedef

commit_message:
Permit overriding the default route for neutron.

The intent here is that the undercloud default route will be discard,
but the router kept for access to the metadata service, and this
specified route will be used for all other traffic.

Change-Id: Idf3f8252c4d4be30839d9d08ad7d4ce49538f04e

commit_message:
Make it possible to set the public interface ip.

This is already supported by the ovs agent, but we didn't need it for
the emulated overclouds. Now we're working on bare metal, it's needed
for some deployments.

Change-Id: Ibb41c40d371e4c153a84fd09c370b158add75b81

commit_message:
Do not use os="..." in Cloud Admin Guide

The Cloud Admin Guide does not profile for the os variable and thus
all occurences of os=... are shown which leads to confusion. Add proper
wording for all examples.

Change-Id: Ib6a651dcfe23cbaad7b727658813c14f36aea73b
Closes-Bug: #1232864

commit_message:
Mention ceilometer in Guides

The Admin User and End User guides include cli references for
ceilometer but ceilometer was not mentioned in the introductory section.

Also, improve markup of the package names.

commit_message:
Fix lost anti_affinity field from Cluster Template

Refactored methods for creating Clusers, so that
default values are applied correctly and parameters
pased to this method are not modified.

Fixes: bug #1232065

Change-Id: I3c3db41a47042e76ad42b01a94d7e3f17a093e81

commit_message:
Another change to parallelize Vanilla plugin provisioning

 * Also changes implementation of context.ThreadGroup: we
   discovered that previous implementation based on Oslo's
   ThreadGroup had broken wait() method: it could exit before
   all threads were finished

Change-Id: I7ae7afa7448852c6e90a942b39de615b209876bc

commit_message:
Add status fields for domains and records

Added a status column in the domains and records tables.
This is part of the asynchronous backends work to allow use to have
record and domains in pending states

Change-Id: Id30756365f8eb2427626b334c2c6119783924679
Implements: blueprint domain-status

commit_message:
Don't reset password by default.

Resetting passwords interferes with post mortem debugging if a new run
was started for some reason.

Change-Id: I60e8f7f5454fa21fd403c51fba7eb15a4c51e35b

commit_message:
Add Neutron support to backend and UI

Neutron networking serialization tests

add metadata_proxy_shared_secret attr

tunnel_id_range and neutron handler fixes

[nailgun] Fix flake8 and fix neutron net_verify task

[nailgun] Add mesh role to Neutron GRE mode

network config save fix

check_networks task stub

neutron config fixed at openstack.json

do not show private for neutron_config GET req

fix data structure in config serializer

check_networks task added

Neutron UI (frontend part)

Change-Id: I0dbdb5237defecd318f72d3242f25960ad2eca8e
